I am a light packer, so I never need more than a backpack, but this squared off rectangular size with deep open center compartment is great for stuffing items. Then there are two good sized zippered side pockets (one on each end) that are very functional. Can be packed to the brim with assortment of stuff. The two smaller zippered side pockets on front are good for super small stuff, but not a lot of it. So think pack of gum, lip gloss, pack of tissues, smaller do-dads.Has handles, or can make use of optional, adjustable shoulder strap.FOR ME: I use this as my DAILY CARRY bag. Not exactly as a purse that I go into places with, but it is my bag that has things I may want/need through the day, as well as some emergency items. I like feeling prepared- so I have snacks, water, a small toiletry kit, first aid kit, and some other goodies. I usually have these items in a similarly sized large baggallini purse , but it always feels just a little awkward. Stuff gets packed on top of each other and it becomes cumbersome to access, with little extra room. But with this shape and style, I have more room to situate stuff, yet somehow it isnt really any bigger than the purse I was using. Things (I used smaller zippered bags- like toiletry sized) are side by rather than stacked on each other. Really good for the items I dont access much but want to make sure I have on hand. THEN there is still room on top for quick grab items- things I will most likely use that day. Maybe I tossed a book on top, or a long sleeved shirt, or some lunch, etc. Love my other brand of purse, but currently I am extra happy with using this Rockland duffle.The aspect that really made me love this is that I can use one of the side pockets to store my smaller baggallini crossbody purse (fits perfect in side pocket). I use that when I want to be totally hands free in a store. Then I can stick my phone, note pad, coupons or whatever in it. Or I use that smaller purse when I am visiting people. I want to have some stuff on me (tissues, lotion, lip balm, cough drops, pads, phone, etc) but dont want to bring in a big purse and set it down. I can keep it cross body. Yet, I dont always want this. Often I pop into a store with just my phone. So I want options. This duffle helps me have my options and keeps me organized.Basically goes like this: duffle stuffed with my basic needs and other stuff that makes me feel comfortable to leave the house and take off in my car or someone elses' car (ie emergency goodies). Small cross body purse stuffed into side pocket for quick grab as needed. I will then leave duffle in car and grab the smaller purse for errands, shopping, appts, visiting. Yet,if I want to carry this duffle as a purse, it isnt so big that it would look funny.Worth trying anyway.I havent had it long, so I will report back on its durability as I use it more.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 19, 2022', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Good Use for the Gym', 'author': 'JECartwright', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'I purchased this duffel bag on a tight budget based on reviews, and it has held up nicely for a gym bag. Maybe I can, like, add super glue to the seams around the phone pouch and replace that clip before it breaks next time.Update October 15 2023: They fixed the zipper on the phone pouch but the pouch still fell apart. The plastic clip is also still a problem. (See pics.)I have now purchased this bag 3 times, most recently in December 2022. This is something I\'ve never done with any other bag or purse, but I really like this one and it\'s nearly perfect for hiking with my dog and general everyday use. (I ditched my purse and started just using this bag for everything a while ago!)On the most recent bag, I was impressed that they had reinforced the zipper on the cell phone pouch. That zipper had broken on my previous two bags and other reviewers had reported the same issue. This newly reinforced zipper hasn\'t broken on me yet.However, one of the fabric edges at the bottom of the phone pouch started separating at the seam only a few weeks after I got it and has only gotten worse with time. I\'ve still been using the thing, lol, but at this point it\'s close to being too big to keep my phone from falling out.Now, if I had applied fabric glue or fray check or even just super glue when it first started I probably could have prevented it from getting any worse and it would have looked good as new, but I just never had the time to mess with it. (Plus, I would\'ve had to use a different bag for at least a day while it dried and I honestly couldn\'t be bothered.)In addition, a few days ago the plastic clip that clips the strap onto the bag - the thing that makes it repositionable from one side to the other - popped apart. (The same thing happened on my previous bag as well.) I snapped it back in, but it\'s happened a few more times since then with increasing frequency. Finally, a few days ago it popped apart again on a hike, dumping my bag onto a muddy trail in the middle of a rain storm, so I finally gave in an ordered a different bag. :(Previous review:I bought this in Feb. 2021 to use for daily 3-5mi hikes with my dog. It was so comfy and convenient that it ended up replacing my purse as well, becoming the only bag I\'ve carried until now (July 2022).I love the convenient phone pocket on the strap, the multiple pockets inside the main compartment, the capacity, and the fact that I can switch the strap from left shoulder to right shoulder. I especially love that it has two water bottle pockets on the sides of the bag that easily fit average sized water bottles, allowing me to carry enough water for myself and for my dog in the summer.There are also multiple places to attach a carabiner clip or S-biner to in order to carry a folding water bowl and a poop bag holder for the pup. To top it all off, the strap is wide enough and comfortable enough to make carrying the bag for long distances a breeze.Unfortunately, about 6 weeks ago the cell phone pocket zipper broke. I\'ve actually still been able to use the pocket by tying a broken hair elastic around the it, providing an elastic restraint to hold my Moto Stylus G5 in the pocket -- as long as I don\'t bend over, it stays put.But then, a few days ago, part of the strap clip popped out. It\'s a kind of plastic rod that inserts into a socket and allows the strap to spin around in any direction, making it possible to switch the strap from left shoulder to right shoulder. Anyway, I was able to snap it back in, but it has popped out a few more times since then, and each time the plastic piece that holds the socket together wears down a little more. So, unfortunately, I\'ll need to replace the whole bag very, VERY soon. (Like, now.)That said, other than those two issues, every other part of the bag has held up impressively well. None of the other zippers have broken and there are no tears or rips in any of the seams or fabric. Both water bottle holders are still intact, despite the mesh material. The bag still looks great as well. And I\'m really not exaggerating when I say that I have beat the crap out of this thing.While I hate having to throw yet another mostly intact thing into the garbage (and from there into a landfill ‚òπÔ∏è), for the price I paid for this bag and the amount of wear and tear it survived I think it was definitely worth the money. title: Travel Duffle Bag 31L Quilted Weekender Overnight Bag for Women with Laptop Compartment, Large Carry On Airport Bag with Wet Pocket & Shoe Bag for Travel, Business Trips, Sports(Black)
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Nice bag / comparison to Vera Bradley Compact Weekender', 'author': 'Shadow', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I got this bag as an alternative to a very nice Vera Bradley compact weekender quilted bag. This bag attracted me because of the padded laptop sleeve (which the VB bag doesn't have) and which I thought might be handy for weekend trips or as a carry-on. To my delight, my 15.6-inch Samsung laptop fit in just perfectly into the special laptop sleeve, a separate zipped compartment that also includes some space for peripherals (space to stash your wristpad, mouse, cords, etc.) plus some mesh pockets for pens or small notebooks, etc. The main compartment of the Bagsmart bag is comparable to the VB bag. There is a big open space with some mesh pockets on one side and a zippered wet pocket on the other (good space for 3-oz toiletry bag for carry-on situations). The VB bag by contrast has mesh pockets on both sides. The Bagsmart bag is approximately an inch taller and two inches longer, so the overall size / interior space beats the VB bag, without making it a markedly larger bag. It should still fit under an airplane seat. The Bagsmart bag and the VB bag are similar in terms of having a trolley sleeve and a number of zipped or open exterior pockets for stashing boarding passes, small snacks, sunglasses, etc. The Bagsmart bags beats the VB bag in terms of having a stretchy open pocket on either end sizes for drinks, a bottle, or a collapsible umbrella (the VB bag just has one). Oh, and it comes with a little shoe bag (nothing fancy, but a nice touch).Overall, the Bagsmart bag slightly beats the Vera Bradley bag in terms of size (slightly larger), exterior pockets (one more), and the laptop compartment (the biggest plus). The Vera Bradley bag beats the Bagsmart bag in being of noticeably better quality, with nicer fabric, prettier interior design, metal rather than plastic hooks for the shoulder strap, and nicer zipper pulls (though both have very similar, high-quality zippers with a smooth feel). Both bags are pretty--I chose lovely designs that I enjoy looking at for both. I love flowers and paisleys, so it's hard to go wrong with either bag here.In sum, I give the edge to the Bagsmart bag because the laptop compartment is just too great of a feature. It enables me to stow my laptop without requiring any jury-rigging or, even worse, lugging a separate laptop carrier; that's going to be super useful for me, both for car trips and air travel. Although I enjoy the superior quality of the VB bag, the versatility and usefulness of the Bagsmart bag will almost surely cause me to choose it when I'm getting ready to head out. Finally, the fact that the Bagsmart bag is *almost* as pretty as the VB bag--yet costs just a third of the price, or less--means it's the clear winner in terms of affordability and bang for the buck, as well.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States October 17, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great for carry on bag, fits under airline seat', 'author': 'Michelle A', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I purchases this specifically for airline travel. I wanted something that would have a dedicated space for my laptop, but also a separate space for few travel essentials. This fit the bill perfectly. I was able to fit my laptop, an additional travel monitor, charging cord, mouse and internet cable in the laptop section. In the other section I put a change of clothes, swimsuit, medications, charging cables, earbuds, tablet, small purse, snacks and water. This bag is well organized with the right amount of pockets. I love how its wider than it is deep. this makes it easier to find stuff. The shoulder strap is comfortable. The back side has a luggage handle strap that you can slide over your roller luggage handle which keeps the bag securely on top of your roller bag while you navigate the airport. I will say this handle strap was a little tight to get over my luggage handle. But that issue is very minor. It has side pockets which are convenient for your water bottle and/or snacks. The zipper pockets on both the front and back are prefect for your phone, passport, boarding pass or other small items you want to access quickly but also keep secure. I was able to fit the bag under my airline seat..with just a couple inches sticking out. The airline did not give me any hassle over this. Quality seems good so far. All zippers glide smoothly (tip: if they ever stick I will just rub them with wax paper). I purchased this in black (So my husband might carry it for me if needed. I know he wouldn't carry a pink bag.) The gold accents really pop against the black. It looks like I spent a lot on this bag, yet it was very affordable. I recommend to others. I travel a lot so I'm hopeful that it stand up to frequent use.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States August 24, 2022', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great Buy, Nice Bag', 'author': 'Mary G.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought 3 name brand weekender bags ‚Äúon sale‚Äù for Christmas presents. They cost over $125 each. I bought this bag for myself for a fraction of that price, and it looks like a much better deal. Lots of space, compartments, nice Zipper, designed to fit over the handle of a rolling suitcase. I love the quilting and the gold hardware. Very nice. Would make a perfect bug-out bag for the car. Appears well-made.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 4, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Great Personal Item, Overnight or gym bag.', 'author': 'Mini Mini', 'rating': 4, 'content': "Loved this rugged little duffle. It's slightly smaller than your average personal item bag allowed on AA so that's a good thing. Fits under AA seats nicely, Even the commuter planes. it doesn't have a shape to it when empty. It's very soft and looks washable.Wouldn't call it a weekender bag though as it is a bit small once you pack what you need for a weekend (clothes, bath, hair & makeup products, shoes etc) but with that said, it's comfy to travel with because of how inexpensive and flexible it is. If it gets dirty, you can probably wash it.it arrives folded flat. You'll think it's a tshirt.. but give it a chance.Has a nice padded area for your laptop and plenty of pockets. I traveled with two computers in that compartment and it was fine. I packed a big thick sweater I was already taking w/me in the big compartment facing the computer side that wasn't padded to protect the second laptop but if you are careful with your bag you don't need to even do that.it is shapeless kind of, but oddly that's also why i like it.I don't expect it to last forever but for the price, it's great for travel, overnight or gym use.Zippers are good quality. Fits plenty of stuff for the size too and has elastic pockets on each side for your water bottles. If you need a bag for your personal item to go with your carry-on, this is quite a good option. I opted for this bag on my most recent trip over a larger more expensive personal item /duffle that is quite boxy. I prefer the lack of structure of this bag because you can squeeze it into tight overhead bins or under the airplane's seat that way.The sleeve to secure it over your carry-on handle has a zipper pocket too. I used this quite a bit.if it's not full completely it has no shape though, so it won't sit very elegantly over your suitcase. I don't care but if you do, keep that in mind. otherwise, great purchase for the price. will eventually be a gym bag. i like it for that too. title: Sling Backpack with RFID Blocking and Phone Holder on Strap for Men Women Crossbody Chest Bag for Travel Hiking
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Very Nice', 'author': 'Alan', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Just received this cross body pack, and I have only tried it on, but I‚Äôm very satisfied with the pack. It has plenty of room for my needs, and I don‚Äôt expect to load it up with a lot of stuff, just basic things I might need that I‚Äôd rather have in the pack and not stuffed into my pants pockets. The RFID pocket is roomy, and the pack itself is very lightweight. I expect it to be very comfortable.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 24, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect', 'author': 'Kim', 'rating': 5, 'content': "We each bought one of these for a trip. They are perfect for both males and females. They have a place for everything, the neck strap is comfortable and doesn't make you sweaty or chafe.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 10, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Low Drag - High Function EDC with RFID pouch that works as advertised.', 'author': 'Aaron Gee', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'I got this to provide a way to discretely keep some bulkier items with me while maintaining a "low drag" appearance. This crossbody sling bag had been perfect. I tested the RFID blocking pouch and it works as advertised. You cannot read cards through it even when holding the reader right on the card. Elsewhere outside of the protection, reading cards wasn\'t an issue.Here is how I set mine up;The front pocket keeps lens wipes, quick wipes, gum, and spare batteries. The quick to use under the snap button pocket holds keys with that keyfob that is too large for jeans. The large zippered pouch holds a first aid kit and wallet and anything else. The second RFID zippered pouch holds my EDC. Sunglasses go in the left mesh bag, flashlight in the right. Phone is in the phone pouch and reading classes looped into the strap on the phone bag. The on body pictures were taken with the bag fully loaded.I\'ve lived with this for nearly 60 days. It\'s easy to carry, looks stylish, and I can put a LOT of small stuff into it without changing the outward appearance. I can have only my keys and wallet and it looks the same if I took everything. All the zippers work well and it\'s the perfect size. not to big and not too small for me (I\'m 6 1 and 210 lbs). The side mesh bags are too small for my water bottle, but I carry that separately.Complaints are few. The zipper on the phone pocket was finnicky once or twice. I\'m rough as hell on my apparel so this may be my fault. Seems fine now. I wish the side RFID pocket on the backside was a little bigger (ie G19 size) and that there was a more robust zipper on it. If that pocket where my EDC goes was bigger and I never dealt with zipper finnickyness this would be a 5 star review.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 14, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Comfortable sling bag with a quick accesses smart phone pocket', 'author': 'W. K. Holton', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I purchased the grey sling bag and the color is very appealing with a nice multi-tone look. The padded strap is comfortable to wear even with a tablet and a good amount of weight. It is adjustable and can be worn on right or left shoulder. The mesh is very breathable and does not cause my back and shoulder to sweat. There are mesh pockets on both sides for quick access. I small water bottle will fit in them, but I wish they were slightly larger to accommodate a larger water bottle. The front pocket fits over your chest and is the perfect size for a smart phone. It makes it easy to reach and very accessible. I hate carrying a purse and have tried many different styles and brands of sling bags, and this one is hands down my favorite so far.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 25, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars WIthstands an hour of rainfall', 'author': 'Qays Poonawala', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I primarily use this crossbody bag for running, but it quickly became a convenient everyday accessory. It has a nice lanyard to hold keys, and a few pockets inside and outside, as well as a cell phone zippered compartment. I don't cary much inside when I go on runs (a pair of gloves in the front pocket, a wallet and keys inside, and a portable charger). While it is uncomfortable to run with a cell phone constantly hitting your chest, I have found that turning the bag so that the opening is forward facing is much nicer; not perfect, because it still will hit you as you run just considerably less noticeable. Living in the PNW, rain is a near daily occurrence, and this bag has withstood light rain as well as the occasional downpour. It did not soak through, which was comforting. The snap that closes the first pocket has become harder to snap after a few months of use. Otherwise it holds up quite well.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 6, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '3.0 out of 5 stars It had all the pockets I needed but seemed awkward and bulky.', 'author': 'Ann Valentine', 'rating': 3, 'content': 'Was not happy with this purchase. As I stated above it felt awkward and bulky and getting anything out seemed inconvenient. I am currently traveling in France and I chose this bag specifically for this trip. However due to the inconvenience I encountered using it I am using a much lighter and more accessible bag on this trip.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 29, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Color and QUALITY are maxed out on this cutie sling', 'author': 'KBJ', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Not much negative to say on this bag. But first, the POSITIVES: Beautiful color!!! I've always stuck with browns for crossbody and blacks for waist packs. But WOW, this is gorgeous...not obnoxiously bright or loud color by any means. Hardware: all of the hardware from zippers, snaps, the swivel clasp...top notch!!!, Material: nicely weighted, durable, easily cleaned of spills. The pack lining also seems very durable. Compartments: a LOT of compartments in a small print of a bag. Endless assortments of pockets/pouches. There is a good amount of padding between selected areas of separation-very nice addition. I like that the swivel clasp can be attached to the right or left bottom of the bag dependant on left/right handed or if you want the pack on the front or back. I would love to see only 1 mesh pocket rather than 2 on the sides...to have the other a solid pocket would be more privacy functional. But, that's my opinion and not necessarily a negative. I think the front zipper would be better for storage of that pocket if it was either diagonal or horizontal more than 1/2 way up. The snap at the top of the bag that accesses the main compartment would be awesome if it was a magnetic snap instead. I love the pocket immediately behind the snap flap before you access the main compartment. The back zipper is great functioning as a Mock RFID, meaning I always keep my credit cards close to my body with all other items between me and other persons in public. So, I love this pocket! There is TONS of room in the central main compartment with additional separate pockets and it zips close so even if you don't snap the outter flap, your contents will be secure. And lastly for the positives, absolutely love that this bag holds so MUCH without it looking like you're on a 3-day hiking trip...it's lays flat against your body. Now the big negative for me personally: there is a shoulder zip pocket for maybe a cellphone, cigs or the like. To access this comfortably, I MUST wear the pack on the back with the main strap across my chest, meaning if I'm out/about and need to access anything from the main compartment I have to remove the pack. If I wear the pack on the chest area, I can't access my cell phone/cigs or whatnot from the shoulder pocket unless I remove the pack. My use for a backpack travel bag is so I can be hands-free when making my way through transportation terminals, fumbling for tickets, or reaching for handrails. Also, in some countries there are lots of stairs in terminals (particularly subways) and dragging a roller bag up and down them is hardly fun. It should be obvious that someone planning long hikes or carrying lots of specialized equipment should probably use an internal frame backpack. I don‚Äôt expect to walk more than a mile or two at any one time with a bag like this. My travel is rather conventional tourism, and having visited all 50 states and 17 countries on four continents I‚Äôve had a chance to work out a minimalist system that can keep me going through any weather, wet or dry, from about 40¬∞F to over 100¬∞F, and for an indefinite period of time. I do not take a laptop, but an iPod or iPad. Everything fits into this Matein bag and a lumbar pack from Mountainsmith.I‚Äôve previously used a book bag as a travel backpack, but being a top loading bag, digging down into it to get what I need is an inconvenience. When constantly on the move, unpacking for one or two nights is a chore, so a bag like the Matein that opens out like a suitcase is a much more practical choice.I bought this bag along with an eBags Mother Lode as both seemed to be good and I couldn‚Äôt decide just from the online info. Both look to be well made, but I kept the Matein and returned the eBags Mother Lode.The eBags Mother Lode has more padding in the shoulder straps but no padding on the back. The padding on the Matein straps is thinner than the eBag but adequate, and it‚Äôs nice to have some padding at your back so you don‚Äôt get completely poked if you don‚Äôt pack right. The eBags Mother Lode came with a shoulder strap and a waist belt, neither of which I need.The overall fit and finish of this bag is quite nice. All of the walls are padded. The zippers look to be rugged and of good quality. I did not have any problems with snagging when running the zippers around the corners of the bag.There is a strap on the back of the bag to secure it to the handle of a roller bag. The shoulder straps are stowed inside a large pocket that could be used for a laptop; there is no separate laptop compartment. The straps attach at the bottom of the bag with metal clips and rings that are easy to operate, in contrast to the plastic ones on the eBags Mother Lode unit, which I found a little hard to disengage. The Matein straps look to be well attached at the top and the bottom rings are sewn into reinforced triangle-shaped flaps that look like they will take quite a bit of stress.The hand straps at the top and side of the bag aren‚Äôt as well padded as the eBags Mother Lode, but considering that this is supposed to be a backpack, I don‚Äôt have any issue with this; they‚Äôll serve just fine.The product description says there are Velcro compression straps inside the main compartment. This is incorrect (The description may have been corrected by the time you read this.). The retainer system consists of four elastic bands that connect in the middle with a clip. This is the only weakness I found in the bag, and was a disappointment to me, and why my rating is four stars instead of five, as the elastic doesn‚Äôt seem much stronger than that in my Jockey shorts, and doesn‚Äôt look like it will last all that long. But in the event that the elastic fails, the external compression straps will more than likely suffice. By the way, compression straps are important. I once took a trip with a large backpack bag that had none and the bag sagged like a plastic trash bag and the contents sloshed around uncontrollably.The secondary compartment of the Matein has two zippered inner pockets and a couple of smaller ones that would be handy for pens and such. There is a smaller compartment on the back (the angled zipper in the photos) that measures about 9 x 11 inches which would be a good spot for the small liquids and other stuff you‚Äôll have to remove at security screenings.The construction of the bag looks good. All the seams are straight; exposed seams are covered with binding, and I found only one loose thread. The bag came packed in a drawstring bag that I think I‚Äôll take along as a laundry bag. Empty, the Matein bag weighs about 2 1/2 pounds vs. almost 4 for the eBags Mother Lode, although the eBags Mother Lode is slightly larger and has more pockets. (One of the reasons I returned the eBags Mother Lode is that I don‚Äôt like lots of pockets.)This Matein bag is about half the price of the eBags Mother Lode and I am so far quite happy with what I see. When compared to the eBags Mother Lode and another nameless bag I saw in a local department store, this is a good deal. I‚Äôll be traveling with it for about six weeks this summer and if I have anything to add to this when I return, I‚Äôll update then.__________Update:Here‚Äôs a follow-up report. I took the backpack on one domestic trip for a week and an international trip for a month. On this latter trip we moved every two nights, and the trip took us through three countries, four airports, numerous busses, boats, trains, taxis, subways, the legendary Heathrow Terminal 5, and the ultimate travel survival test, the London underground during afternoon rush. The pack survived well. I remain disappointed with the flabby elastic retention straps on the inside, but the exterior ones took over and kept things under control. I‚Äôm a minimalist traveler ‚Äî the pack was roomy enough for all my stuff excepting a few things I carry in a small waist pack. The pack came with a thin bag I used for laundry; and it folds in half easily to be stored in its original box. Nine times out of ten, if you‚Äôre at the gate with a rolling carry-on, you‚Äôre going to get targeted for weight (carry on AND personal item can only weigh 7kg or 15 pounds). Scales are everywhere and it‚Äôs a gamble every time. You‚Äôre likely going to get pressured to check the bag because of the age-old excuse of being ‚Äúoverbooked with a full flight.‚Äù The first picture shows the two bags we purchased. I slid mine in bottom first and still had a size-able slot on the side to either stretch my feet or to put a small crossbody pouch. Not really knowing how much space I‚Äôd have on this first use, the third pic shows the little pouch I used. Next flight I‚Äôm going to bring a small crossbody. Pictures 2 and 3 show the nice ability to use the 4 clips on the sides of the bag to compress the bag itself and the pics also show you that you don‚Äôt have to join the general panic to get in line just to fight for overhead space - it‚Äôs one of the best parts of this bag. We went through a lot for my fiance\'s new suit (between the cost and many alterations), so I wasn\'t going to risk it (or my dress) getting ruined or lost, so flying out there this bag was a carry-on. Going through the airports, I had it on top of my rather small roller bag via the rear handle "strap" and it was great until I actually boarded the flight. This particular plane had narrower aisles, so I had to take the bag off of the roller bag which made it a little awkward to go down the aisle with my roller bag behind me and holding this bag in front of me. As my fiancee only had a small shoulder laptop bag, on the connecting flight he carried this on the plane instead while I managed my roller bag. It fit fine in the overhead compartments, and these were Southwest 737 Max 8\'s. On our return flights I checked the bag as I wasn\'t as worried about the suit as I was on our initial flights (as he likely wont need it again and because if it got lost the airline would have to reimburse us). But as some people complained about the plastic zippers, out of caution I did get some wire-shanked TSA locks and secured the zippers together. As the metal on the zippers isn\'t large enough, I wound the wire through an opening in the well-stitched nylon zipper pulls (with the clips on the end) but I "double-wrapped" it to make sure the zippers were held tightly together (if it only went through once there would be a wide gap due to the length of the lock wire). On the side where the top zipper goes across I was able to pull the wire through the end of the metal zipper pull as well, and that one I also wound through twice. I was skeptical that the bag would be able to make it through being tossed around by TSA and other bags being stacked on top of it, so to give it some extra stability I cable tied the handles together to help hold the bag together in case the top zipper started to give. This bag was the first of ours to come off the carousel at baggage claim and I was surprised it was in amazing shape. I was very very impressed. I don\'t know if/when I\'ll need to use this bag again, but I feel confident that it will hold up. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great travel purse', 'author': 'JGB', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I really like this bag for travel. I have had trouble in the past with pickpocketing and am paranoid about having my belongings stolen. The security features are what drew me in on this product and they did not let me down. The security clasps gave me confidence that my wallet was safe in the clasped pocket. The purse itself holds a lot of items and is quite comfortable. I was able to fit my hydroflask water bottle and a foldable rain jacket inside the bigger purse pocket along with a portable phone charger, pocket calendar, tissues, and a few other small items. I can even fit a thin book or journal in this bigger pocket! A small wallet, a checkbook, a passport, and some pens or pencils can fit in the smaller pocket with the card slots. And the front pocket can fit a phone for quick access, or other small items like chapstick or something that is frequently accessed.I was disappointed to discover that the water bottle pocket on the side is not big enough to securely hold a water bottle. A normal sized, disposable bottle may stay well, but anything bigger/taller will be too tall to not fall out. Luckily the inside pocket is big enough to store a bottle. The other side pocket is the perfect size for a pair of sunglasses or a small snack.I will say that the slash-resistant strap, while useful in protecting against an attempt at purse-stealing, can be a bit sharp on the shoulder due to the stiffness of the material. The body of the purse is also water-resistant in the case of rain (at least a light rain, although a heavier rain might seep through more).Overall, I absolutely love this purse and its incredible functionality. I love having my things organized and this purse provides all the necessary pockets to keep them that way.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 27, 2020', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Second time buying this bag!', 'author': 'Alison L.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I love this bag -- it\'s the second time I\'ve bought it! Had an earlier model of the same bag that I used regularly for years, but had to retire it recently after two of the zippers finally gave out. There have been some changes and improvements to the current model being sold. 1) Magnet closure on side pocket replaced with Velcro closure. This is a good improvement as magnets have no place on handbags (and the earlier version erased my bus pass on one occasion). 2) Lobster-claw security clasps have been replaced with rectangular hinge clasps. This is a mixed change. The new clasps are easier to use, but may be slightly less secure. The new clasps are probably less likely to break, but due to how they are attached, they\'d be harder to replace if they do break. 3) Two interior mesh pockets in main compartment have been removed. Generally this is a positive. The mesh tended to catch on things, and there are still two cloth pockets that hold my phone and glasses. This frees up more space in the main compartment. 4) A sturdy ribbon with clasp has been installed in the main compartment -- great for easily finding your keys. 5) Middle wallet compartment now has a interior zip pocket, similar to the larger one in the main compartment. This seems more secure and more functional than the earlier model\'s small open pocket. 6) Credit card slots have been moved to the other side of the middle wallet compartment, outside of the cash pocket. This works fine. 7) Cash pocket is slightly smaller than the one on the earlier model. Works OK for dollars, but might be harder for some foreign currencies or placing a bank envelope. 8) Gusset added to wallet compartment. This makes it easier to open this compartment and access your items. 9) All three zippers seem to have been upgraded to stronger, sturdier ones. Bodes well for preventing the main reason I had to give up my earlier bag!If I could make one suggestion for improving this bag, it would be to re-think the side pockets. The one with the Velcro closure is really too small for securely holding a phone, and the zippered one on the other side, allegedly for holding a water bottle, is really not functional for holding anything other than a mini water bottle, which most people don\'t bother to use or carry in a bag. I think it\'s OK to have at least one side pocket for holding small items you want to access quickly, but I think an open envelope pocket on the back side of the bag, for holding papers or realistically stashing a phone, would be more useful.Although I\'ve made a lot of critiques here, I have to say that I love this bag and do highly recommend it. I originally bought it before travelling abroad, but ended up using it as an "every day" bag. The security features help me feel more protected wherever I go, and it\'s just the right size for holding the things I need to have with me. I look forward to more years of using this bag!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 2, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect everyday bag', 'author': 'celeste gonzalez', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This fabric is easy to clean. This should help anyone who was stuck between both bags like I was, to make a decision.üòäüòäBrands: I purchased the Bolosta bag ($37) and the Wogarl bag ($44), both cream-colored. The Bolosta bag has way more reviews so it was my first choice in the beginning. I‚Äôm glad I decided to buy both and compare because the differences are astounding!Dimensions: The Wogarl bag‚Äôs dimensions are (L)19.7 x (W)9.8 x (H)14.6 inches and the Bolosta bag‚Äôs dimensions are (L)19 x (W)9.5 x (H)13 inches. This means the Wogarl is the bigger bag.Cream Fabric: The first thing I noticed is that these bags are quite similar at first glance. The cream material on both bags is exactly the same texture, color, and quality. It‚Äôs quite nice and durable. This section is a tie!Leather: The Bolosta bag had a darker brown leather-like material that looks more artificial and cheaper than the leather on the Wogarl bag. The leather on the Wogarl has that aged, hyde look that leather tends to have and looks just like real leather. Wogarl wins this section if you‚Äôre looking for a more quality look.Shoe Compartment: The Wogarl bag has a much bigger shoe compartment than the Bolosta. I could probably fit two small shoes in the Bolosta but fit two large shoes or even three small shoes in the Wogarl. Also, the Wogarl is lined with a thick, silky material as opposed to the thin fabric in the Bolosta. Wogarl wins this section.Leather Strap: The leather straps on both bags are the same length and structure, however I like the Wogarl strap better since the leather material looks more quality. Wogarl wins this section.Zipper and Hardware: The Bolosta zipper is made with the leather material but the seams and thread is coming out so it looks cheap (pic included). The Bolosta hardware has a brushed gold finish. The Wogarl zipper is regular metal but feels durable. The hardware has a brushed steel finish.Front side: The front-sides of the bags are similar. The Bolosta has a plain face with one open pocket compartment. The Wogarl has the brand name etched on a piece of leather on the face of the bag. It also has 2 compartments, an open pocket and a zipped pocket. The space in the open pockets on both bags is the same. Because of the extra pocket the Wogarl has, Wogarl wins this section.Back side: The back-sides of the bags are exactly the same. There is a zipped pocket on both and an open space for a suitcase handle to pass through. The space in the pocket is the same on both bags. It‚Äôs a tie!Handles: The leather handles on the Bolosta are much smaller than the Wogarl. The Wogarl handles are thicker, maybe 2x the size so they feel more quality. Both bag‚Äôs handles have a leather strap that holds the handles together. The Wogarl‚Äôs strap fits tighter and more secure around the handles since the handles are thicker. Wogarl wins this section.Interior Space: The space in these bags are exactly the same. I included a picture where I put my cosmetics bag in both of the bags and you can see that the cosmetics bag takes up the same amount of space in both the Bolosta and the Wogarl. It‚Äôs a tie!Interior Fabric: There is a massive difference. Bolosta has a thin, cheap-looking material üòí but Wogarl has a silky-satiny, soft, thick material with a nice sheen. This material looks and feels quite expensive. Wogarl wins this section.Interior Zip Pocket: The Wogarl has 2 zipped pockets, one lined with waterproof material and one lined with the silky fabric. Bolosta has 1 zipped pocket. Wogarl wins this section.Interior Open Pocket: Both bags have two open pockets but there are some differences. The Bolosta pockets are made with that same thin material but the Wogarl pockets are double-lined with the thick, silky material and also have a leather detail at the edges. Wogarl wins this section.Weight: The Wogarl is so much heavier than the Bolosta bag. This helps because it adds to the quality, expensive look. The Bolosta is quite light. I looked up the weights on the product pages. The Bolosta bag is 2.6lbs but the Wogarl is 2.95lbs. It feels even heavier than that, honestly. Wogarl wins this section.In conclusion, it‚Äôs no doubt that the Wogarl is the better bag. It looks more quality and expensive, it reminds me of my Polo Ralph Lauren bag. It also has more compartments and better looking and better feeling fabrics. The Bolosta in contrast looks and feels so much cheaper. Between both bags, it looks like more thought went into making The Wogarl since the fabrics, structure, size, textures, and features look more expensive than the Bolosta. It looks like it costs three times the price that I paid for it! I‚Äôm gonna go ahead and keep the Wogarl. I‚Äôm not sure why the Bolosta has more reviews, maybe it‚Äôs been on Amazon longer and it‚Äôs $7 cheaper than the Wogarl. But I think over time, people will realize the Wogarl is the better option. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Excellent travel bag!', 'author': 'Sarabear TX', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Schlepped this bag all over Europe and it holds a surprising amount of stuff! I was able to stuff it with quite a lot of items (a change of clothes--nothing worse than arriving without your checked luggage, book, iPad mini, sweater for the flight, snacks, quart bag with liquids, etc. etc. etc.I did not need to unzip the bottom for extra space, but was glad to have that feature.I did use the snaps on the side--I guess their purpose is too make the bag look smaller?? The snaps came unsnapped right away when I used the bag straps, so that was a worthless feature. I think a loop button feature would hold better for that purpose.There are 3 pockets on the front. I had a water bottle in one (will hold a plastic 16.9 oz. bottle--probably not the wider reusable bottles, though), my book, small magazines, and such in the middle, and gum/candy in the other pouch.The best part, though, is in the back. Yes, that gap was wide enough that I could easily fit the bag onto the carry handle of my suitcases (both my smaller hardside carry on and my larger suitcase). I love that! The zipper pouch is big enough for a passport. I did have a few other flat items in it, but don\'t overstuff it. The passport will fit easily, but should go in first, as the outer edge with the zipper will partially cover it before you zip it closed.I noticed one reviewer complained that it didn\'t work with their bag--but they were using a very soft-sided bag under it. If you are going to stuff this bag, it will work best on a sturdy piece of luggage (hard or soft-side)--not a "mushier" soft bag.That said: with this bag (which was well stuffed, mind you), it did sometimes make my carry-on bag tip over if I wasn\'t careful, and the 4 wheels of my carryon didn\'t run as smoothly. I just used 2 wheels when moving at a clip, and that was fine.The bag did really well and still looks great. I had enough room under the seat to put a foot on either side of the bag (under the seat in front of me).The color I wanted (black with brown handles) came with a "wash bag" (toiletries bag). I didn\'t end up taking it, but I kind of wish I had. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Love it!', 'author': 'Nana banana', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This is a sweet bag that I wasn‚Äôt sure about when it arrived but after opening and seeing how perfectly it fits over the handle of my carryon bag, I am sold! Appears to be water repellent material.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 15, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Handy for Layovers', 'author': 'Sunny', 'rating': 4, 'content': "The Green is a beautiful mint and cream color. The inner sleeve is the right size for a tablet, NOT a laptop. Despite that, this bag is VERY handy in an airport. It's a standard bag size but it's roomy enough to fit a lot of stuff that you are going to want within reach at an airport. It's also expandable via a zipper on the bottom, giving you a few additional inches height. It has 4 inside pockets, the Velcro sleeve, a large pocket that I used for e-cig supplies, including batteries, charger and e-liquid, and just outside that pocket are 2 more smaller pockets, perfect for carrying phones. There are 3 pockets in the front, one has a zipper, and there is a small pocket in the back of the bag, sized for I.D.'s, credit or debit cards. There is an area, behind this outer pocket, that is where you would attach the bag to your luggage handle (assuming you have other luggage). There are button clasps on both sides of the bag. I have no idea what these are for, but I guess you could attach items to the sides.I was able to fit my laptop (in the center of the bag, not the velcro pocket), a neck pillow, jackets, phones, snacks, sweatshirts from the airport gift shops and more. This fit underneath the seat in front of me, so it was handy on every flight. I was also able to use this as a pillow during the long layovers, just have something soft inside. The laptop sleeve is padded and provides extra protection for your electronic devices. The bag is made of high-quality and durable materials, ensuring it will last for many trips to come.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 21, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect bag for my arts & crafts- as I like to do crafts outside the home as well as in', 'author': 'Jeneane Vanderhoof', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I needed a bag to organize my arts and crafts- not just for storage in the home but a lot I do outside- at a nursing home, a hospice, and friend\'s homes- are some of the places where I often do crafts (and need to carry things to do them with me). While this bag is perfect for travel and carrying the necessities you would need for all kinds of trips (up to a week-long)- it is also the perfect craft bag.One of the reasons I say this is because of how it looks- to me when I saw it- it looked like a craft bag because of the colors.The neutrality of the green and how it\'s bright but not too bright- just says "crafting" to me. And it\'s a perfect combination with the cream.This bag comes with a zipper along the bottom and when you unzip it you have almost double the space you had before you unzipped it. The depth of this bag seems unending.... So while this bag is perfect for an overnight trip- when you have a weekend or weekly trip- you unzip the bottom and have tons of room!Of course, storing arts and crafts and transporting them- I have unzipped the bottom of the bag and left it that way for quite some time. But, I am making my way through many of the projects that I store there, so when I have less, I plan to zip up the bottom- and make the bag smaller. Bags like this are great because they are easier to store- as they get smaller when you need them to.I love how the carry straps look (shiny) and feel (smooth)- they make this bag easy to transport. I think another reason why I chose to use this as a crafting bag was because it didn\'t come with a shoulder strap. So this is not going to be a bag you want to lug around for hours or hours (unless you can handle bags like that well- lucky you ;)- because, remember, you only have the hand straps. However, depending on how much you have in the bag, the hand straps are long enough that you can carry the bag on your shoulder.Inside there is a padded separator where you can store a laptop or tablet- however please know that I don\'t believe it can fit over something that has a screen bigger than 12 inches- my 11.6-inch screen laptop fits inside but with very little room to spare. On the opposite side, inside the bag, there is a zippered pocket.The front and back of the bag also have zippered pockets which I love- and also on the front, on each side of the zippered pockets are open pockets where you can store things you need to get quickly. That means on each side I can store a paperback but anything bigger- won\'t likely fit there. I do put my cell phone there often (to get to it quickly) as the pockets are pretty deep.A note on the photos I attached with my review- I had used this bag for a month when the photos were taken- so please know there is a little wear and tear on it (and it looks like it was photographed on Amazon when it arrives to you). The pictures are taken with the bag in its largest carry capacity- meaning it is unzipped on the bottom.If anyone has any questions about the bag, please feel free to reach out and ask.Thank you', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars A travel bag that has room to brag', 'author': 'MJ', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Got this bag for use as a personal carry-on item, and very happy with the size and design. Should be able to pack a good amount of stuff in its roomy main compartment. Add in the smaller pockets, and it's perfect. One of these is even plastic-lined for wet things.Easily earns 5 stars from me...", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': "4.0 out of 5 stars I'm kindof loving it!", 'author': 'Music Lover', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'I ordered this bag in grey, and I really love the color. It\'s almost like a blue/grey. I wasn\'t entirely sure if I\'d like the white (which is actually cream) part on top but its actually stylish and doesn\'t stick out as much as I worried.The thing I like most about this bag is its zippers, which are very high quality and not at all cheap as some other, similarly priced bags I\'ve seen. Also, the handles on the bag are decent length, where you would be able to carry it over one arm without any issue even when completely full (also not common in similarly priced bags). The last thing that sets this bag apart from others is its fabric, which is not "shiny" or cheap looking like I worried. It\'s not terribly thick, but its at least double-lined, and I think this will last.Now for the areas that it could improve:The inside has a zippered compartment, and two "cubby" compartments right below the zipper that are not zipped. If you put something inside both the zipped compartment and the cubbies, I\'m not sure much would be able to fit into either, since they overlap within the bag. On the other side of the inside, there is a little pouch but it just includes a simple single velcro across its middle - obviously this won\'t keep anything from falling out (although the velcro is also good quality and not at all flimsy). I wish they had just had one size with a zipper and the other size with the cubbies/velco. Finally, the openings on the outside front, which thankfully do fit my 1-L reusable size water bottle, should be directly on the side as opposed to the front. This makes it a bit awkward to carry the bottle, and almost impossible to shove the bottle in if the bag is completely full. All in all, its the best bag I\'ve tried at this price point!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 19, 2023', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Can‚Äôt wait to travel with it!', 'author': 'katy', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'Seems like a nice travel tote bag, with a couple exceptions. I tested it with a couple of sweatshirts and a toiletry bag and even without the extension, all fit comfortably with tons of room to spare - I think I could pack for a weekend in here, especially with packing cubes. With the extension open, there‚Äôs quite a lot of space.Pockets: I would not trust the front pockets to hold a water bottle without falling out unless it‚Äôs quite a small one. Mine seemed like they were going to fall out. The front zip is a good size for my kindle, and the back zip would hold a passport. I‚Äôm not sure I would put anything *actually* wet in the ‚Äúwet‚Äù zip pouch inside, as the lining is the same material as the rest and not especially thick or waterproof seeming, but I‚Äôd probably put toiletries in there and feel okay. Laptop slot is a good size.This is a ‚ÄúFoldies‚Äù dupe type bag, except it does not actually fold up. There is also no cross body strap, just over-the-shoulder straps, though they seem strong and comfy. There are buttons on the top sides as if to help with folding, but as far as I can tell they don‚Äôt have a function.There is a bit of a plasticky smell upon opening, which I hope will dissipate over time.Overall it seems like a good bag for traveling, but perhaps not the most durable in the world. We‚Äôll see after I bring it on a trip.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 9, 2023', 'is_verified': False}]

title: Travel Backpack, Large Carry On Backpack, Personal Item Travel Bag, Airline Approved 17 Inch Laptop Backpack,College Weekender Business Hiking Bag, Beige
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Good design is my obsession. Here is a winner!', 'author': 'DiscerningConsumer', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Got this right before leaving overseas. I had it loaded enough it wasn't going to fit under the seat, but probably could have if I'd not absolutely filled it. There are many manufacturers of these type of travel backpacks. I was looking for a very rectangular one without pockets that would be useless to me. I already owned several regular backpacks and wanted one that would fully open and allow easy access for clothes, shoes, toiletries, and electronics while on the go. The shoulder straps were ample and could be hidden away if you were using it as a suitcase. The strap across the back worked well to secure the backpack to my suitcase handle. One slender full length compartment was generous to accommodate a fleece jacket folded up. (Also could serve as a wet container, if needed) Another slot stowed a laptop, located against the back, with lots and lots of padding. Another area held folders of information. Also there were small envelope sized compartments. I actually used the plastic rectangular containers that came with the backpack. I should mention that the bag was tightly wrapped up and had a very strong odor. I left it fully open and didn't notice it after a day, which I was relieved to find. There are straps inside to secure the load if it isn't large enough and there are straps on the outside that cinch down the load to make it look smaller. One bottle holder on the side. Nice handles on top and side making it easy to grab. The exterior material was substantial. Laptop at the back allows better balance. There is also a zipper to expand the bag, although I really didn't use it except briefly. An extra inch or so? A sister had a smaller bag and that fit easily under the seat. If I had required it to get under I would have had to squash the bag down some. But for day to day it was great. Zippers worked easily and none of that digging through a backpack that didn't open all the way to the bottom. Nice that several other slots also opened fully. Main considerations are size needs and exactly what you will want: more or fewer pockets on the outside, more or less rectangular. While not so delightful a color, black is impervious to travel schmutz. Did wipe up nicely after I had to keep my feet on it in the car. Wish I had discovered this model sooner. I spend a good deal of time reviewing various others and found this one ideal for me. title: Travel Backpack, Large Carry On Backpack, Personal Item Travel Bag, Airline Approved 17 Inch Laptop Backpack,College Weekender Business Hiking Bag, Beige
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Good design is my obsession. Here is a winner!', 'author': 'DiscerningConsumer', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Got this right before leaving overseas. I had it loaded enough it wasn't going to fit under the seat, but probably could have if I'd not absolutely filled it. There are many manufacturers of these type of travel backpacks. I was looking for a very rectangular one without pockets that would be useless to me. I already owned several regular backpacks and wanted one that would fully open and allow easy access for clothes, shoes, toiletries, and electronics while on the go. The shoulder straps were ample and could be hidden away if you were using it as a suitcase. The strap across the back worked well to secure the backpack to my suitcase handle. One slender full length compartment was generous to accommodate a fleece jacket folded up. (Also could serve as a wet container, if needed) Another slot stowed a laptop, located against the back, with lots and lots of padding. Another area held folders of information. Also there were small envelope sized compartments. I actually used the plastic rectangular containers that came with the backpack. I should mention that the bag was tightly wrapped up and had a very strong odor. I left it fully open and didn't notice it after a day, which I was relieved to find. There are straps inside to secure the load if it isn't large enough and there are straps on the outside that cinch down the load to make it look smaller. One bottle holder on the side. Nice handles on top and side making it easy to grab. The exterior material was substantial. Laptop at the back allows better balance. There is also a zipper to expand the bag, although I really didn't use it except briefly. An extra inch or so? A sister had a smaller bag and that fit easily under the seat. If I had required it to get under I would have had to squash the bag down some. But for day to day it was great. Zippers worked easily and none of that digging through a backpack that didn't open all the way to the bottom. Nice that several other slots also opened fully. Main considerations are size needs and exactly what you will want: more or fewer pockets on the outside, more or less rectangular. While not so delightful a color, black is impervious to travel schmutz. Did wipe up nicely after I had to keep my feet on it in the car. Wish I had discovered this model sooner. I spend a good deal of time reviewing various others and found this one ideal for me. Price was right too.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States May 4, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great for traveling', 'author': 'Ana H.', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'It is the perfect size for traveling. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great Product for Price & Purpose', 'author': 'BethM', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'We used this stroller bag to cover our new Britax B-Ready Stroller, Black double stroller on a trip to Disney in 2012. It is the only bag on the market we could find that fit the B-Ready. We did have to take the back wheels off, but with the B-Ready this is really easy and caused no problems whatsoever. When we were ready to board we just popped the wheels off and shimmied the stroller into the bag. The baggage handlers commented that they liked the handle and the red color (which was easy to see as a gate checked item). When we arrived in Orlando, the bag was ready for us at the gate. The bag itself had a HUGE smear of black grease all along the front. I was nervous about opening it up, but I am happy to report that the stroller inside was pristine!! No dirt or grease marks at all. Without the bag, our stroller would have been completely stained (our stroller is light silver).That said, I agree that the material is flimsy and the bag won\'t last more than a few trips. The material frays and there are some holes; it clearly isn\'t designed to "pad" your stroller either. We have used it twice (two round trips), and I am about to purchase a new one for our next trip as our current bag is ready to be retired. But jeez, people. What do you expect for $10??? Suck it up and by a new one after a few flights. I did take the advice of a reviewer of this one or the umbrella stroller bag & used duct tape on the seams prior to the flights. I purchased both the umbrella stroller & the car seat bags & both held up well--no rips or tears & no damages or dirt added to baby equipment. Even hubby thought this was a good idea AFTER he saw another dad pick up their gate-checked stroller (without a bag) have a bunch of stuff fall out of the stroller since they hadn't emptied the basket before gate-checking. Nice to know that if the towels came loose from the harness, since the harness wasn't super tight w/just 2 towels, that they wouldn't get lost since this bag can be closed.This bag did what I expected, kept my car seat clean!I did end up checking the car seat but the airline was nice enough to take the car seat in this bag (turned inside out so that 'GATE CHECK' wasn't visible) and put into a large clear plastic bag to protect from any rain (since it was rainy weather when we traveled). title: TAILI Travel Compression Bags 10 Pack, Roll Up Space Saver Bags (5 Large, 5 Medium), No Vacuum Needed Reusable Packing Bags for Luggage, Suitcase, Backpack, Travel Essentials
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Love the different options to remove air', 'author': 'Megan', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I have used a variety of storage bags and I can tell you, regardless how much you spend on them, what the brand is, etc. they are plastic and it's easy to accidently puncture and break or get a small hole. Always be careful handling them for best results.Although these seem thin (like most other bags) they are able to hold a lot and really hold when you suck the air out of them.I got the 8 count, the bags a giant! They would be a good size to store under furniture or if you have really large containers or spaces to store them in. They are great for large amounts of clothing, thick bedding, pillows, etc.It even came with a pump (or whatever you'd call the opposite) that you can use to remove air. You have the option to manually squeeze air out of the bag, use the pump or a vacuum. I've got a upright shark vacuum that worked great to remove the air, the pump was also much easier to use then I expected. The most difficult method is the manual of course, it's a large bag so it can be challenging to get all the air out especially if your smaller. *I have only tried laying items horizontally in the bag so far and not with the bag vertical like shown in pictures so this could effect how easy it is to manually remove air.I was able to fit the huge pile of smaller bags (another brand) of toddler clothing in just 2 bags with room to spare. I was able to fit the 2 bags under half our queen bed where they continue to remain just as compact as when I placed them a few days ago (as I said before be cautious if you have a metal frame to not bump into any protruding pieces that may puncture the bag).I tried one bag on our bed pillows, we have 2 standard pillows with shames, a medium size lumbar pillow and 2 small square pillows, all of them fit in one bag easily and I was impressed at how flat I was able to get the bag (using the pump).A little tip you can label your bags with a sharpie and just use some rubbing alcohol if you ever want to remove or change the label.Definitely something I would get more of in the future.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 25, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Holds so much& saves space', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I can‚Äôt believe how much these hold and how much they compress! If they open my suitcase or it breaks open, all my belongings are securely stored.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 10, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars These Bags are Amazing', 'author': 'Christy Jankowski', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'I had my doubts. The included clips worked perfectly.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States November 21, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars So Impressed!', 'author': 'Flfez7', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I purchased these to store holiday bedding and throw pillows for 3 bedrooms. title: VMstr Travel Vacuum Storage Bags with Electric Pump (USB Pump + 8 Combo Bags)
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars The Large Black Pump is Very powerful and fast! The small ones, not so much...', 'author': 'Faith', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I tested the following 4 pumps:Black, large, DC Powered:https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07JGMHP62/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1Black, Removable USB Cable powered:https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07KJJHWLP/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1White, Attached USB cable powered:https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07QCWW84T/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1Black, Battery powered:https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07T3P7Y8P/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1--- Review of Black, large, DC Powered ---The largest black edition of the pumps offered here is VERY powerful and fast acting! It removes are 5-6 times faster than the little USB and battery powered pumps offered on Amazon. See the photos for a comparisonI conducted 2 experiments, seeing how long it took to suck 2 different sets of bags completely empty of air:1 minute - A medium sized bag with one flat pillow in it5 minutes - A jumbo sized bag with 1 flat pillow, one extra large king size puffy pillow, 2 king size sheets, and a medium sized blanky.Pros: Very fast, extremely powerful, removes all air from the bag.Cons, large, bulky, heavy, and requires a proprietary DC wall adapter to power it. However, it was still able to easily fit in the side pocket of my backpack which I traveled with it on multiple international airplanes packed like this, and had no problems. It just adds a little extra bulk and weight.--- Review of Black, Removable USB Cable powered ---This was tied at the 2nd fastest pump, but significantly smaller and slower at removing air than the large pump.Using the same experiment:5 minutes - A medium sized bag filled the same as above28 minutes - A jumbo sized bag filled the same as abovePros: Small, lightweight, removable USB cable allows you to use a shorter or longer cable as desired.Cons: Very slow at removing air, compared to the large pump.--- Review of White, Attached USB cable powered: ---This was tied at the 2nd fastest pump, the exact same size as the small black pump.Using the same experiment:5 minutes - A medium sized bag filled the same as above28 minutes - A jumbo sized bag filled the same as abovePros: Small, lightweight, non-removable USB cable (can't lose it).Cons: Very slow at removing air, compared to the large pump, non-removable USB cable (can't use a shorter cable, but can make it longer using a USB extension cable).--- Review of Black, Battery powered ---This was the same size as the other 2 small USB powered pumps. It was very, very slow at removing air. I didn't conduct the same test, because I gave up due to how slow it is. However, it was probably the same speed as the 2 USB powered cables I tested, now that I realize how slow they are as well. It was about the same. I may try the test again in the future if I decide I want a battery powered pump.Pros: Battery operated, can run while charging, small, lightweightCons: Very slow at removing air, battery will eventually die after a few years.------------------------Overall, I am keeping the large pump for use at home, and I may even bring it with me on traveling. I like the idea of using a lightweight, 5 times smaller pump... but I don't like the idea of it taking 5 times longer to pack.The main reason is that usually I need to pack in a hurry when I'm traveling, to catch a flight or taxi somewhere. If I have to vacuum seal 5 bags with the large pump, it would only take me 2.5 minutes per bag on average (using a mix of small, medium, large, and jumbo bags), which nets me just under 15 minutes to pack all my bags.That same load would take around 75 minutes to pack using the small USB or battery powered pumps... which makes me unlikely to use them in reality. The only place I could use it being useful is on an airplane, since I like to bring pillows and blankys in the cabin. I could then vacuum seal it before unboarding the plane and pack it back in my carry on.This wasn't possible with the large pump due to the fact that it has a wall mounted power adapter, and the plane only offers USB power, or the proprietary plane jacks. I just resorted to manually laying on my vacuum bags and forcing the air out when unboarding the plane, which worked well enough to stuff it by force back into my carry on. A little USB pump would help make this process much easier, though, Lol. I suppose I could bring one of the manual hand vacuum pumps on board, even though they take a long of physical stamina, they work pretty rapidly and effectively.So, I haven't decided if I'll keep any of the little ones yet. It would be either the black USB powered, because of the replaceable cable, or Black battery powered if I do. Although, the white USB powered pump was just as good, but there has to be some deciding factor.I hope this review helps you in your selection of a nice vacuum pump!!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States September 21, 2019', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Works great. Already paid for itself.', 'author': 'Ralph777', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought this vacuum pump/bag system for my most recent vacation. It was really easy to use and worked well. The bags sealed shut and kept a vacuum for the entire trip. It does take a little while to pump all of the air out of the bags, but I expected it to take some time with the small pump. I was able to condense all of my packing for my week-long trip to just my carry-on bag and backpack. It paid for itself by allowing me to eliminate a the cost for a checked bag for my flight. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Love the different options to remove air', 'author': 'Megan', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I have used a variety of storage bags and I can tell you, regardless how much you spend on them, what the brand is, etc. they are plastic and it's easy to accidently puncture and break or get a small hole. You have the option to manually squeeze air out of the bag, use the pump or a vacuum. I've got a upright shark vacuum that worked great to remove the air, the pump was also much easier to use then I expected. The most difficult method is the manual of course, it's a large bag so it can be challenging to get all the air out especially if your smaller. *I have only tried laying items horizontally in the bag so far and not with the bag vertical like shown in pictures so this could effect how easy it is to manually remove air.I was able to fit the huge pile of smaller bags (another brand) of toddler clothing in just 2 bags with room to spare.
