Shipping was overnight so that was a plus!!!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 7, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Best space saver EVER!', 'author': 'Amazon Customer Paige', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'These are seriously the best things ever, especially for traveling! No vac needed, so can be used again on your way home, and again and again! The three different sizes were so perfect for packing different types of things which kept me super organized the whole trip when looking for things (instead of digging through my suitcase). I basically put all my pajamas/tshirts/leggings in one, all my dress clothes in another, casual tops in one, jeans and casual bottoms in one, under garments/socks/tights in one, then all team sportswear in another (I went to Vegas for the 2024 super bowl). Then on my way back I was able to put all my dirty clothes in one bag so they didn‚Äôt stink up the clean clothes I didn‚Äôt end up wearing! I FIT SO MUCH in my suitcase it was amazing!! Another thing I was surprised about was nothing really wrinkled oddly, I brought a wrinkle spray just in case, didn‚Äôt have to use it once, my dad and brother had to use the whole bottle for there clothes!!!HIGHLY RECOMMEND!The clips might come off, but are super easy to put back on!‚ÄúTaylor Wynn‚Äù on YouTube has a great in depth tutorial on how to use them and what to use them for while she was traveling internationally! The video is called ‚Äúpack with me for travel‚Äù or something! She also has links to all the things she uses in the video, which is how I can across this product!You WONT be disappointed, I promise!!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 3, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great value and quality', 'author': 'Amy', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I purchased a set for our home to store blankets, comforters, etc. Items that take up a lot of space that you may not need daily. The bonus with this is all of the different sizes. Several will be used for travel. I didn't use the included pump yet, as I had my vacuum available. Highly recommend. Would buy again. Have purchased for a gift for my nephew moving across country. He had never used them before and was quite impressed. For several days he would tell anyone who would listen about these magic bags that are such a space saver! lol", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 13, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '3.0 out of 5 stars Suction Bags Great, Roll Up Bags Not So Great', 'author': 'Trippet', 'rating': 3, 'content': "I got these to store my sweaters and free up drawer space for my summer clothes. I learned how to crochet and am finally up to making sweaters so my pile has grown significantly. I was quite pleased with the compaction when using the pump. I now have a solid brick of sweaters that fit between my dresser and my wall.I am going to use the bags for my yarn, too. What better way to keep the yarn fresh, dust-free, moth-free, and organized than to squish it all down?! I got the idea from a post wherein the poster showed how their yarn had arrived vacuum sealed. We all had a good laugh, but then we all thought . . . this is brilliant! No longer will I accidentally use this skein or that hank for a project when I had purchased it for something else. If I have to table a project for a bit I can seal it up, with the hook, so everything stays together. For smaller projects I'll use my food sealer, but for blankets these bags are roomy enough.Now, the travel bags were a disappointment. I rolled and rolled and rolled, and I felt as though the bags would burst before they would blow out air. They simply don't work as well as the pump bags. It's a nice thought, but execution is lacking.Someone mentioned spraying Febreeze in their bags before sealing. On one hand it's clever, but on the other I'm thinking it would Have to completely dry before sealing, and I don't have that sort of patience. A dryer sheet, sachet, or a soap sleeve, though . . . there's potential there.My biggest concern with traveling with sealed bags is TSA. If those guys decide to have a peek in my bag and unsealed it, what a mess that could be!Clothing Definitely wrinkles. Most hotels have irons these days, but I'll caution that a wrinkle release spray may be a good idea to pack.The other issue I ran into with travel was the length of the bag once sealed and pumped out. The bag is quite inflexible so it's difficult to fit into a bag and one must plan carefully when arranging clothes in the bag prior to pulling the air out. Mine also did not flatten, but curled. That made for wasted space in my bag for our return trip. I may have overstuffed and likely should have brought along a second bag. I didn't realize it was going to be in the 50s in Vegas and we would need to purchase additional clothing to be comfortable. I used a carry-on sized bag, which is normally more than sufficient for 5 days, even for a gal; however, with those additional clothes and souvenirs (and lotions I got hoodwinked into purchasing /sigh) I found myself having to get creative, and I had to unzip the extender for the first time.I'm traveling again so if I use the bags and find that two works better than one, I'll update. The pump fit fine so I tossed the roll up bags to the side and took the pump with me instead. I do recommend getting an electric pump. It was quite the work out, and not too pleasant with arthritis and herniated discs. I survived without serious injury (only a crick in the neck that wouldn't go away), but an electric pump would have been appreciated.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States April 13, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Worked great', 'author': 'Jpeyton', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I bought this so that I could air seal stuff for our trip to make more fit in our suitcases. It held up great and was perfect for what we needed. I like this brand compared to a lot of other ones. Other ones I have tried do not hold up, but this one actually stays sealed nice and tight.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 14, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Easy to use and great price', 'author': 'Lili Rags', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This is an AMAZING product for travel or storage! Its truly a no brainer to buy and would buy more once we need it. Its so easy to use and any vacuum can be used to seal it.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 7, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Worth the Purchase--No Vacuum or Pump Needed', 'author': 'All.smiles', 'rating': 4, 'content': "Bought these compression bags for my son's day trip only using a carry on & personal bag as we didn't want him to check in luggage and it wasn't going to be possible without these bags. I mainly used the large one as we were packing mostly winter clothes. For example, in one large bag I was able to pack 5 fleeced line pants and 10 pairs of socks (men size clothing, my son is 5'11). Once everything was all packed, I tried following the instructions but it didn't work that well for me, but the bags did work on how I did it. I wasn't able to really roll the bags due to the thickness, so what I did is zipped most of it and left a little section open for air to come out and then I pressed on it, then I folded it in half to remove more air and once I felt all the air that I could remove was out I completed the zipping. I was amazed on how compressed it came out. So on a carryon we were able to pack a total of 7 fleeced lined pants, 3 hoodie sweaters, 6 shirts, 10 boxer briefs, and 10 socks in 3 compression bags.For his personal bag (a backpack that I purchased from Amazon) We compressed a winter jacket also purchased from Amazon and a vest and still had room to add his personal hygiene items, snacks, 2 phone batteries. With these bags there was no need to check in a luggage and it all worked out! Loved them and will definitely use for future trips, especially for myself bc I'm an over packer...haha! I suppose you can also use for storing item around the home, best part is that I didn't need a vacuum or pump to suck the air out!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 10, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Saved a lot of space both in the closet and the suitcase', 'author': 'K P', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I was heading to Canada and unsure about which winter coat I would need (the temperature kept drastically changing). To make matters worse I was trying to pack just a carry on with 2 winter coats and a pair of heavy winter boots. I purchased these bags so I could vacuum seal my heavier coat so I could bring it as back up without taking up too much room. It was easy to seal the bag and suck the air out; however the manual pump did take awhile and sometimes the seal part got stuck on the fabric and I had to maneuver it differently to suck more air out. I would prefer bags with an electric pump. I tried a couple of vacuums, but nothing but the manual pump worked.I was so pleased by how much it reduced the size, that I then stayed up late to vacuum seal some pillows and a queen size comforter. I tried the included travel bags where you roll the extra air out of them. While this worked, I can't say it really saved much space and I wound up not bringing these bags with me. They probably would work better with something puffy like a coat rather than just sweaters.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 6, 2024', 'is_verified': True}]

Nice bag, good quality, almost kept it for myself!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States November 27, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': "5.0 out of 5 stars Well designed, solid quality, can't wait to use!", 'author': 'BethLakshmi', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I'm often on the go, between workouts, performing arts, and splitting my time between two homes - this looks like a GREAT product and I can't wait to use it.What I really like is that it feels solidly built (I'm very destructive) but it isn't heavy. And it's well laid out to hold your stuff securely in both folded up mode and expanded into a hanging configuration - the big pockets are deep and have elastic bands to secure bulkier, heavier bottles. The smaller pockets are narrow enough to keep your smaller items from shifting, and yet I think there's enough space in the folded up configuration to let you stuff this really seriously full. And the fact that it has 4 separate zipper seal compartments should keep any bottle exploding to a contained zone.Took a good look at the zippers - which were gold, giving the whole thing a nice lux look - and they also look pretty indestructible. But the real test is going to be filling it (overfilling it?) a few times and subjecting it to the trunk of my car - an endless source of trauma and jostling. Will post back here if I ever manage to do damage. :)So far - great product for a somewhat accident prone person on the go!UPDATE - after first trip! - I used this as my bag for all liquid/gooey/spillable cosmetics when I flew from the East Coast to Puerta Vallarta - not a short trip and not always gentle checked bag handling. It was a solid product. I packed a BUNCH of fun self care stuff, it all fit well, and made the trip both ways without any goo penetrating the rest of my luggage. I DID have an explosion of a pot of foot creme, and it was well contained in one of the larger compartments of the bag, and easy to clean with a wet washcloth.It hung up well in the hotel room, and that's where I learned how helpful the elastic bands are - when it hangs, you really want to use them to keep bottles upright, as the weight of the overall container will distort it a bit, and it's easy for everything to get jumbled up. I have some short/weird shaped bottles, so that was a bit of a trial and error process to get stuff to sit in the bag well enough to be accessible - but not a big problem.Totally a winner of a product on a long trip where you want all sorts of goop to protect and nuture your skin and hair!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 26, 2024', 'is_verified': False}]

title: Anti-theft Classic Slim Dbl Zip Crossbody Bag
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars HIGH QUALITY BAG', 'author': 'Laurie', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I was looking for a nice travel crossbody bag for my upcoming 2020 Alaskan cruise. I was drawn to this bag because of the features and a few colors. I ended up getting it in black.This bag has very nice safety features that is awesome for traveling and an alternative to carrying a huge purse. I cruise alot and this is a great choice when u get off the ship.The bag is very light. The back of the bag has a pocket but doesnt have any closure. It measures about 8 1/2 inches deep. It could be good for documents or items u need to reach quickly. The front of the bag has 2 zippered pockets. The great thing about the zippered pockets is that it connects and locks to a hook on the side of the purse. This helps prevent someone from unzipping ur bag. Both pockets measures about 4 inches deep. The top of the bag has a zippered closure. It measures close to 10 inches deep. The purse has an inside zippered closure pocket that measures close to 6 inches. The other side on the inside of the purse, there is a section that has credit cards slots. It has RFID technology. The other inside pocket is large enough for maybe a cell phone, pens or whatever u like. The inside is light grey and the material feels like a rain jacket - possibly waterproof without feeling plastic. The outside of the purse is made of some sort of waterproof material. The bag and strap is slash proof. The strap end has a hook that locks to the bag.Overall, I am excited about this bag. I cannot wait to use it. The price is reasonable especially given the features. This bag is very plain and basic looking but is a powerful little thing.I will leave another review after it's used. I attached pictures to help with ur decision. I give it 5 stars due to quality. But if anyone is uncertain, give it a try.UPDATE: 6/14/22 - This is an update since 2020 when I first purchased the security bag. I've been using this bag for several trips as a travel bag. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Smaller then expected', 'author': 'Susan Brown', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'They fit a lot more than it looks. While the concept of compressing clothing to save space is appealing, the execution falls short in practice. The cubes themselves are well-made and durable, with sturdy zippers and quality materials. However, the compression feature doesn't always deliver the desired results. While some items compress nicely, others seem to resist compression entirely, leading to frustration and uneven packing. Additionally, overfilling the cubes can cause the zippers to strain and even break, limiting their effectiveness. Despite these drawbacks, the cubes do help to keep belongings organized and prevent wrinkles during travel. Overall, while the Compression Packing Cubes offer some benefits, they may not be the go to storage saver they initially appear to be.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 20, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars An organized way to travel!', 'author': 'Pamela', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I have wondered about these packing cubes for years and finally decided to take a look. Gorilla Grips is a favorite brand, so I was confident the cubes would be a well made product. Traditionally I have more or less made my own packing cubes by using very large 2.5 gallon ziplock bags, about the average size of a clothing cube. In my ready to go one night suitcase, I had one ziplock bag with houseshoes/nightgown/robe and another with a change of clothes for both myself and my husband. I transferred these to the two largest cubes; they fit easily and in fact I was able to add another item or two to the biggest cube.I didn't discover the cubes had two zippers until later. I packed with the compression zipper already closed! But it worked, I just had to tug harder to get the first zipper around the bags. But it would have been much easier had I realized you unzip the compression zipper first.The cubes appeal to my desire for tidiness, but I did lose the clear windows of the ziplock bags. So I'm faced with two bags without a hint of what is in each of them. I could fix that by making laminated labels. I might even buy another color and separate my clothes from my husbands. One day of night clothes and underwear and outerwear would definitely fit in one bag. Of course for longer trips you'd probably want to separate the outerwear and underwear and nightgowns into different bags. I used the 3rd smaller cube for some of my costmetics - no real compression there.Did they save room over the ziplocks? I'm not sure, probably at least a little. Were they neater, more pleasing? Definitely. And for sure easier to open and dress out of than ziplocks!I am undecided if I want to go further in the Gorilla Grips cube world. I don't travel that much. If I did, I'm pretty sure I'd also try the Gorilla grip cubes with a mesh window. That product doesn't have the compression zipper, and it is hard to tell if the compression is less. But the mesh window gives a hint of what is inside and lets the items breathe a bit. Then I'd outfit my husband and I with color coded cubes with whatever product seems to work best for us.This product is very reasonably priced, and it's worth the small investment to enter the cube world. Another well crafted product from Gorilla Grips!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 27, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Excellent space saver for organized packing', 'author': 'Kent Li', 'rating': 5, 'content': "This package of 3 compression packing cubes is exactly what I need for my upcoming Italy trip. They arrived neatly zipped up and folded into themselves, and I was a little worried they were the wrong size, but opening the package showed they were just as described, and how compact they could truly be!Each packing cube has a handle for easy carrying when full, a main zipper to open the compartment (with zipper pulls so it can be opened and closed separately from each direction), and a zipper to compress the packed cube. I like the zipper pulls on the smooth closing zippers as well. The material is lightweight, which is excellent for travel, and seems easy to clean off, yet durable. The inside seams look clean, though there were a few long threads dangling on the inside - I recommend trimming these so they don't get snagged in the zippers. I I have the light grey color, which allows me to see the clothes through the material.Now to answer - does compression really save space? See my pictures and you'll be able to tell how much it really does save. I have photos numbered 1-6:(1) These are the 14 adult size medium lightweight t-shirts into the medium sized cubed(2) I easily put in 2 stacks of 7 shirts side by side(3) It easily sipped shut, and I used my hand to show the size of the pack when closed.(4) Then I applied the compression by zipping up the compression zipper. You can see the compression works and makes the packing cube much more compact.(5) I've always rolled my shirts when I pack, so I decided to try it again. I rolled the 14 shirts, each layer fit 7 shirts just as easily as before.(6) I zipped it closed and applied compression. WOW! THIS IS THE WAY TO PACK - it's much more uniform all around and less bulgy so it will be easier to arrange in the luggage.I think this assortment of sizes is perfect as I'll be able to pack intimates in the smallest cube, shirts in the medium cube, and pants/jackets in the lighter cube. I highly recommend this set to anyone who wants to organize their packing and save space in their luggage for souvenirs!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 22, 2024', 'is_verified': False}, {'title': '1.0 out of 5 stars To small', 'author': 'deb shearer', 'rating': 1, 'content': 'Color', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 28, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Take Everything You Need in Less Space', 'author': 'Macsandy', 'rating': 4, 'content': "I got the 6 piece set in the turquoise color. I used them to pack for a 9 day trip (varied climate/temperature) with everything in just one medium suitcase and my backpack. I took 6 pairs of slacks and one pair jeans; 7 blouses/shirts; all underwear; a raincoat, sweater, and windbreaker; 9 pr. socks; 3 pair of shoes (flats, flip-flops, and dress). I was not sure it would all fit but these compression packing cubes made it possible. After folding and fitting items into a bag and zipping it up I could then zip up the other zipper and everything would be compressed down to 1/2 to 2/3 the original depth.The zippers seemed quite sturdy through the process and didn't feel like they would break or separate. Whether the items wrinkled or not seemed to depend on the fabric, but for the most part nothing was too wrinkled to wear after a little shake out and some Downy Wrinkle Release.The only thing I would change with these bags is the length of the corded pulls on the zippers. They are so long that they get in the way. Other than that I like everything about these bags.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 15, 2024', 'is_verified': False}]

reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Perfect luggage organizers!', 'author': 'April Strickland', 'rating': 5, 'content': "These are so worth it! Quality construction, Great design, EXCELLENT ZIPPER...made me a BELIEVER in PACKING CUBES!!', 'author': 'MightyDwighty', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Pros:- Quality build- Excellent zipper quality and durability- Strong seams- Lightweight- Open netting design allows for visibility of contents and easy compression- Attractive but simple colors and design- Comfortable zipper pulls- Comes with sack to carry all the packing cubes and can alternatively be used as a travel laundry bag- 4 packing cubes for the price of many competitors offering 3- Excellent customer serviceCons:- Nothing major at the moment, but I am starting to notice after a few months of use that some of the seams appear to be stretching a little too far and am concerned that it may tear after a while- The plastic spring cord lock used on the sack that carries all the packing cubes (I used the sack as a "dirty laundry bag") broke after a monthPersonal Experience:Ask me a year ago whether I would ever have packing cubes and I would have scoffed at you and declared that it was illogical to try to save packing space by using packing cubes that forced the cube shape. Now...I\'m a believer!!Packing cubes have changed the way I packed forever. Not only does it organize everything I pack (underwear, socks, pajamas go in one; shirts and pants go in another, etc), it allows me to pack 2-3 times more than I used to be able to because you are able to squeeze everything into a packing cube and then zip it up. Packing cubes don\'t add any appreciable weight to your luggage because they are so lightweight anyway. And for longer trips, I simply take out my packing cubes from my duffel bag/suitcase and they serve as drawers for all my travel items.In terms of Shacke Pak specifically, I referenced in my "Pros" why I think Shacke Pak is generally superior to other brands. In particular, I received one packing cube that had an issue with the zipper that resulted in the zipper handle breaking pre-maturely. I contacted Shacke Pak and customer service immediately sent me a replacement packing cube without any hassle. I am very pleased with the customer service and it has given me some measure of confidence that they will continue to take care of their customers in the future.**Update: I also own two sets of eBags packing cubes (you can read my other reviews) and have had the opportunity to compare them directly to Shacke Pak. In all honesty, both brands make exceptional packing cubes and you really wouldn\'t be disappointed either way. But to be nit picky, I will share a few of my observations:- Shacke Pak uses a material with a matte finish compared to the more shiny honeycomb design of eBags. The Shacke Pak material stretches ever so slightly, whereas the eBags material has very little give. As a result, it appears that the material eBags uses is slightly more durable, but Shacke Pak looks slightly more premium.- Shacke Pak uses hidden stitching beneath the zippers, whereas eBags uses a double stitched design in most places. After owning the Shacke Pak packing cubes for about a year, I am noticing that the hidden stitching under the zipper pulls a little more and actually becomes visible when I pack the cubes tightly. This concerns me slightly and makes me question the long term durability whereas eBags\' double stitched design seems to hold strong regardless of how tightly I pack the cubes.- The depth of Shacke Pak packing cubes is .75" to 1" more, so you can pack more.- The zipper pull handle (not the zipper itself) on one of my packing cubes from Shacke Pak fell off after one month. I contacted Shacke Pak and they immediately sent me an entire new packing cube. Shacke Pak demonstrated excellent customer service, but at the same time I am a little concerned that something like that happened so quickly in the first place. Since then, I have had no issues with my two sets of packing cubes from Shacke Pak. I have had no issues with eBags in terms of the zippers or zipper handles in the 6 months that I have owned them.- Shacke Pak packing cubes gives you 4 for the price of approximately 3 from eBags. Also, Shacke Pak includes a pouch with the packing cubes that can be conveniently used as a dirty laundry bag when you\'re travelling. You seem to get a little more for your money with Shacke Pak.- Zipper quality for both is excellent, as they both use YKK zippers.- Overall: You can\'t go wrong with either and each brand has slight advantages over the other in a few areas. I personally think eBags is slightly more durable, but that Shacke Pak is slightly more attractive and gives you a little more for your money.Conclusion:If you are looking for a high quality and durable set of packing cubes for travelling, you really can\'t go wrong with the Shacke Pak set. The price is reasonable and you get 4 packing cubes for the price of what most competitors charge for 3. I have not had any real issues with quality or durability (I travel and use these a lot, but I will update my review in the future), and Shacke Pak has already demonstrated to me that they have excellent customer service. I also think the Shacke Pak packing cube set provides one of the most stylish designs compared to the others out there.**I have included a picture of one my packing cubes when it is packed tightly showing what I mean about the hidden stitching being stretched and visible. This concerns me a bit.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 30, 2015', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': "5.0 out of 5 stars If you haven't purchased packing bags before I would highly recommend them!", 'author': 'Loni', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'I had a friend recommend packing cubes when she heard my husband, two year old, and I were going to Europe for two weeks and staying at 6 different hotels. I looked at a variety of options when typing in "packing cube" and finally decided on the Shacke Pak brand and Bago brand.I chose the Shacke Pak brand because I liked that it offered four different sizes and it being my first time purchasing these I wasn\'t exactly sure what sizes to get. I also liked that with Shacke Pak it came with a laundry bag, which definitely came in handy, because there were times we got rained on all day and with our full packed trip and we didn\'t have time to find a washer and dryer, so it was nice to separate some of our dirty clothes in the laundry bag. I also really liked the biggest size that it came with and was able to pack almost all of my clothes in just the biggest size for a two week trip!The reason I chose the Bago brand was because I liked that you had the option to choose all of one color or two different colors. The organizer bags are a lot thicker than your regular ziplock bag, which is what I have usually used, so these will last a lot longer, and there are multiple sizes, so I could separate our toothbrushes and paste in one and soaps and lotions, etc. in another. I really like the biggest size that came with Shacke Pak, the Bago ones I purchased only offered two sizes that were the two middle sizes offered from this Shacke Pak purchase.Also, I should mention, I purchased brands different from what my friend recommended because these were half the price and honestly, I loved both of them and thought they were very durable. title: Personal Item Travel Backpack For Women Men Airline Approved Carry On Backpack Flight Approved Waterproof Sports Luggage Backpack Casual Daypack Small Hiking Backpack
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Lightweight and great for weekend traveling', 'author': 'atxanon', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I bought the standard sized grey-blue backpack for traveling as my carry-on item. The color is very cute but might get dirty over time since it's a light color. I've been using a North Face backpack for years to travel with before I bought this one. This one is much roomier and has so many pockets and it fits perfectly under an airplane seat with room leftover!. The previous backpack I used was a lot heavier too even without anything in it.There's a laptop sleeve and a compartment for shoes which is a huge plus. FYI if you use the shoe compartment, there will be less room in the backpack. The water bottle holder is tiny as I couldn't fit a slim water bottle in it so I just used it as another pocket.You can even plug in a portable charger to the backpack. I connected a portable charger in the inside of the backpack and was able to connect a USB-A charging cable in the port on the outside of the backpack to charge my phone with easy access without having to take the portable charger out. You cannot use a USB-C cable with this backpack (USB-A ports only)! Make sure the portable charger also has a USB-A input to connect to the backpack.I haven't tested out the water resistance with the material on the backpack yet but I think the material is pretty durable. I was able to fit at least 3 outfits and a toiletry bag + other small items in the various pockets. I highly recommend this backpack for weekend traveling/traveling light! If you need more room, I would get the larger size (pretty sure it can also fit under an airplane seat).", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States September 29, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars multi-functional and well made', 'author': 'Mark G.', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I wasn't sure what level of quality I would get from this due to the price but bought it based on the reviews. I was pleasantly surprised. The zippers seem very sturdy and it holds quite a lot. We bought for a cruise trip and they worked perfectly. They are sized so they fit within airline size restrictions as a personal item so you can fit them under seat and take a carry on. They were handy for shore excursions for use as a day pack especially the compartment for wet items/shoes. The straps are padded well enough to be comfortable when stuffed full. I also like the strap that allows you to hang it off the handle of your rolling carry-on. Family members on our trip liked them so much we gifted some for Christmas. Very happy, good product.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 25, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars A great addition to my travel luggage!', 'author': 'Surfer girl', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Loved the space and compartments of this bag. It's absolutely as advertised, durable and packed a lot of room for so many things. It can even fit under an airline seat in a pinch as long as it's not TOO stuffed. I loved being able to put my laptop in the bag and all he little books and crannies for storing things. The shoe bag is a nice addition but does take up some room inside, so have to be strategic if packing for many days. Loved that the water bottle holder stretches easily even with a fully packed bag. The luggage handle strap is also an added bonus if you're hauling a roller bag as well. A great value for the price. Happy traveler!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States January 28, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Needs more easy access space. 3 stars overall, 4 for the value.', 'author': 'Save the Bees', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'This is a great backpack that passes as a personal item on most airlines including JetBlue & United. Fits under the seat. The suitcase configuration is nice & the wet pocket is a nice addition. Found the backpack comfortable and aesthetically pleasing. However; the shoe pocket can really only be used with sandals or if the main compartment is nearly empty. I love the color (I got peacock blue) and the material feels a bit hydrophobic, so it‚Äôs easy to wipe down. I haven‚Äôt put it in the washing mashing but a friend confirmed that the USB port was still functional after the backpack was washed. I also appreciated the padding on the back and the ‚Äúsecret‚Äù compartment against the back to prevent passport theft.If you travel frequently you might want to go with something higher quality. But this pack is good for the price.This backpack would be a lot better if it included:Higher quality straps. The straps look and feel a bit cheap. The stitching does not appear too sturdy and will definitely begin to separate quickly with consistent use. I used mine once; and it already started fraying. A handle on the side of the bag, allowing for it to be carried briefcase style and a larger (or maybe two?) water bottle sleeves would be great.A loop or two for hanging keychains on the outside of the back. Doesn‚Äôt seem important until you need a place to hang a hat or a neck pillow.Most importantly this backpack needs a better configuration for the laptop pouch & the two slim front most pockets.The laptop compartment doesn‚Äôt have a sleeve or strap, it‚Äôs just one slim pocket. That isn‚Äôt a big deal, but it would be nice if the laptop pocket could be opened suitcase style for TSA/customs purposes. If the laptop pocket had a clear sleeve / Velcro strap like most backpacks & if the pocket could be opened full length, you would not need to remove the electronics from the backpack.Finally, the most inconvenient feature on this backpack is the complete lack of quick access pockets. There is literally not a single pocket you can easily drop your phone or wallet into. If the front of the backpack had a full access arched zipper pocket, even if it was super thing it would be SO helpful. A few mesh organization pockets (like in the main compartment) and an attached key ring inside the front most pouch would go a long way.So overall, get this backpack for casual travel as a budget option. But the lack of accessibility definitely makes it incompatible with daily use. With a better front pocket and just a few minor and easy adjustments, this bag would be a 10/10.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States September 1, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars 4.5 Stars - Almost perfect', 'author': 'Brice', 'rating': 5, 'content': "This is really a great bad. High-quality materials, it is professional enough to bring in a meeting, is super water resistant, and holds a ton. It stands up on its own and is carry-on compliant. title: Tote-A-Ton 32.5-Inch Duffel Bag, Turquoise, Single
reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great for international moving or flying with hiking backpacks', 'author': 'J.J', 'rating': 5, 'content': "I originally bought this bag to protect my huge 65 L backpack during air travel. It was really difficult to carry around the airport when so heavy, but it was a price I was willing to pay. My boyfriend didn't think this bag was a good idea and bought a bag specifically made for air travel with backpacks, and his had no handles so it was impossible to carry and also ripped, so he won't be using it again. My bag came through the whole trip and both flights in pristine condition, and I now use it all the time to go between home and college when I don't have time or am too lazy to pack nicely. I throw everything and I'm good to go. I've never run out of room with this bag!Now, a year later, we are buying this bag again (in the same pretty turquoise color) because my family had an exchange student this year and she needed another suitcase to bring home all of the clothes and belongings she acquired this year. They stuff inside of a their pocket and measure approximately 8x10x2. EMS\'s bag is $49 and 38" long. REI\'s bag is $29 and 36" long. After purchasing both I found the Samsonite Tote-a-ton and returned the more expensive bags. The tote-a-ton is cheap in $ but not in quality. The durable material is the same as the more expensive duffles with two sturdy handles to lift. There\'s outside pocket and inside pocket, too. I have an Osprey Aura AG 65L. The pack is approximately 31 inches long. It fits perfectly into the duffle with room to spare. I haven\'t actually packed the backpack but feel confident it will still fit into the duffle. I am packrafting in Alaska this summer. I need something that will safely get my backpack and gear to Alaska. While in Alaska I will use my backpack for day trips/rafting and my gear will go into the duffle which will be hauled, by the outfitter, to the next location. Perfect solution! Plus, in the future, when I travel and don\'t need the duffle, it collapses perfectly and can be stuffed into my pack without taking up a lot of space. I have a friend traveling to Nepal in March. I showed her the duffle and she\'s purchasing one to protect her backpack, too. Great deal. We\'ll see how it holds up in June and I\'ll report back then :-)UPDATE July 14, 2015:I just returned from my 10 day trip to South Central Alaska. The duffle was perfect for this trip! Just like I mentioned above...the duffle protected my 65L when I checked it on the plane and then I used it to store my gear and clothing while using my backpack for packrafting during the day. The placement of the zipper made the bag easy to get in and out of. I\'m not sure how well the material will continue to hold up because it is rather light weight. It was pretty dirty after being checked on the plane. I don\'t travel regularly so it may be a while before it gets used again. However, the light weight factor can be a plus if you are backpacking and have to stow the duffle in your backpack. I\'d still highly recommend it!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 13, 2015', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Will purchase again!', 'author': 'Amazon Customer', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'This bag is more roomy, beautiful and durable! Overall Impression: These are decent travel laundry bags for the price I paid (which was just under $9 for two). I would return them if I had paid any more than I did. I don't think they will hold up well for regular or frequent use unless you're willing to do some minor sewing (or some other kind of modification to reinforce parts of them). They would likely last thru at least 1-2 small trips and may actually hold up to several uses each time before eventually falling apart or needing some amount of repair. Do not buy these if you absolutely do not want to take any risk of a seam coming undone and your laundry or other items spilling out. (But if you're willing to do some minor sewing, these bags seem like they could be pretty sturdy.)Material Quality: 5/5.Both the bag and handle fabric seem to be of good, strong quality. They're appropriate materiald for the size of the bag and the amount of laundry it is meant to hold. The black bag material feels a tad bit thicker than the gray bag. You can faintly see colorful clothing thru the gray bag in a decently lit room. However, the material is dense enough that you can't make out any graphic designs or stains on clothing. The draw string cord is thick, has a good length, and has a sturdy plastic push-button clasp on it. (Sorry... I'm not sure what those things are called. But they work well on both bags and don't seem like they'll fall apart with normal use. They keep the draw string top shut, but also tie the cord off as an extra precaution.) The zipper is okay. It's not heavy duty, but it's good enough for it's intended use, which is to contain the folded up laundry bag for storage or to hold very light items.Construction: 2.5/5.The sewing/stitching needs improvement in at least one important area. There is a very tiny part on both bags that is not sewn together at all (or hardly at all), which will likely cause the bags to fall apart quickly. The area is at the top of a side seam, located just under the drawstring opening. I noticed another reviewer mentioned this problem. So, I suspect this is a common design flaw and I didn't just get two faulty bags. This area definitely needed extra stitching to reinforce the top of the seam on both bags and to help hold together the draw string pocket on the gray bag. Luckily, I'm not to bad at hand-sewing and I happened to have the right supplies on hand. It was still a bother to have to take the time to fix these things. I'm also not sold on how much weight the bags can actually hold (with multiple use) based on overall construction. The bag handles seem sewn on well enough for light, infrequent use. But I feel an extra row of stitching could have been added to make them more secure.*I've included a video that show the problems I noted.Bag size: 5/5.One of these bags seems large enough for 3-7 days travel, depending on the time of the year and the size of the traveler. I'm a slender woman (Ht: 5'6, Wt: 115 lbs, usual clothing size is XS/S or a 4 in US womens). I was able to fit about 4 light winter outfits into one bag and close it without any hassle. (One outfit was basically equivalent to light to medium thickness denim pants, thin base layer leggings, underwear, bra, thick wool socks, a tank top or very slim fitting shirt, and a very oversized flannel or oversized medium thick sweatshirt.)Other possibly helpful info: I bought these bags intending to use them regularly as a space saving solution in a small home. (This is why secure handles were an important consideration for me.) I am currently hanging the bags by their handles from a slim bathroom door. I'm using these bags to store my dirty laundry in and to carry them to laundry room when full. (I have a hanging fabric laundry bag that is way larger than these ones, but it buldges out too far as it's filled. It's also not designed to be removed from the hangers and can be quite heavy when full.) I can hang both of these bags on a single door, one above the other, at convenient heights. However, they do buldge out when full since the fabric is thin and they don't have anything firm to keep them structured. They're convenient for sorting dark and light laundry into as I fill them up. I'll probably continue to find a better solution for my small space, but these work better than my previous laundry bag for now. These bags would also work well to hang from a bunk or loft bed given their size. A full bag can easily slide under my bed which has about 14 inch clearance underneath it. I have an extra large laundry machine so I may not want to wash a load of clothing until both bags are full. And I do sort my laundry by color and/or item type before washing, so I may look for other similar and cheap bags to purchase. These bags are a great size for traveling, in my opinion. I will definitely use them for that purpose once I find a better solution (and now that I've sewn them so that they're more durable).I don't think I'd buy these bags again... only because I don't want to have to take the time to inspect them and reinforce the weak areas. I may consider going thru the hassle again IF they end up holding up very well after several months of regular use, and I need some travel laundry bags for me and other family members.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 17, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Great for travel', 'author': 'KelRelyea', 'rating': 5, 'content': "We travel a lot, and there's always the problem of how to separate your clean and dirty clothes on longer trips. These are great for stashing in your suitcase to keep things neat.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 25, 2023', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Nice Laundry bags!', 'author': 'Marie L. Verderame', 'rating': 5, 'content': 'Love that there are two since I usually split my clothes into light and dark fabrics. But you could also use as a his and hers! This was just the size I was looking for. I previously had one that was too large and one that was too small! But this was the ‚Äújust right‚Äù!', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States March 2, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': "4.0 out of 5 stars I don't like them", 'author': 'Jack', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'Free to good home', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States February 5, 2024', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars It looks sturdy but haven‚Äôt used it yet', 'author': 'lk808', 'rating': 4, 'content': 'It looks sturdy and it‚Äôs the right size to hold several days worth of clothes.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States December 21, 2023', 'is_verified': True}]

reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars The Large Black Pump is Very powerful and fast! It removes are 5-6 times faster than the little USB and battery powered pumps offered on Amazon. See the photos for a comparisonI conducted 2 experiments, seeing how long it took to suck 2 different sets of bags completely empty of air:1 minute - A medium sized bag with one flat pillow in it5 minutes - A jumbo sized bag with 1 flat pillow, one extra large king size puffy pillow, 2 king size sheets, and a medium sized blanky.Pros: Very fast, extremely powerful, removes all air from the bag.Cons, large, bulky, heavy, and requires a proprietary DC wall adapter to power it. However, it was still able to easily fit in the side pocket of my backpack which I traveled with it on multiple international airplanes packed like this, and had no problems. It just adds a little extra bulk and weight.--- Review of Black, Removable USB Cable powered ---This was tied at the 2nd fastest pump, but significantly smaller and slower at removing air than the large pump.Using the same experiment:5 minutes - A medium sized bag filled the same as above28 minutes - A jumbo sized bag filled the same as abovePros: Small, lightweight, removable USB cable allows you to use a shorter or longer cable as desired.Cons: Very slow at removing air, compared to the large pump.--- Review of White, Attached USB cable powered: ---This was tied at the 2nd fastest pump, the exact same size as the small black pump.Using the same experiment:5 minutes - A medium sized bag filled the same as above28 minutes - A jumbo sized bag filled the same as abovePros: Small, lightweight, non-removable USB cable (can't lose it).Cons: Very slow at removing air, compared to the large pump, non-removable USB cable (can't use a shorter cable, but can make it longer using a USB extension cable).--- Review of Black, Battery powered ---This was the same size as the other 2 small USB powered pumps. It was very, very slow at removing air. I didn't conduct the same test, because I gave up due to how slow it is. However, it was probably the same speed as the 2 USB powered cables I tested, now that I realize how slow they are as well. It was about the same. I may try the test again in the future if I decide I want a battery powered pump.Pros: Battery operated, can run while charging, small, lightweightCons: Very slow at removing air, battery will eventually die after a few years.------------------------Overall, I am keeping the large pump for use at home, and I may even bring it with me on traveling. I like the idea of using a lightweight, 5 times smaller pump... but I don't like the idea of it taking 5 times longer to pack.The main reason is that usually I need to pack in a hurry when I'm traveling, to catch a flight or taxi somewhere. If I have to vacuum seal 5 bags with the large pump, it would only take me 2.5 minutes per bag on average (using a mix of small, medium, large, and jumbo bags), which nets me just under 15 minutes to pack all my bags.That same load would take around 75 minutes to pack using the small USB or battery powered pumps... which makes me unlikely to use them in reality. The only place I could use it being useful is on an airplane, since I like to bring pillows and blankys in the cabin. I could then vacuum seal it before unboarding the plane and pack it back in my carry on.This wasn't possible with the large pump due to the fact that it has a wall mounted power adapter, and the plane only offers USB power, or the proprietary plane jacks. I just resorted to manually laying on my vacuum bags and forcing the air out when unboarding the plane, which worked well enough to stuff it by force back into my carry on. A little USB pump would help make this process much easier, though, Lol. I suppose I could bring one of the manual hand vacuum pumps on board, even though they take a long of physical stamina, they work pretty rapidly and effectively.So, I haven't decided if I'll keep any of the little ones yet. It would be either the black USB powered, because of the replaceable cable, or Black battery powered if I do. Although, the white USB powered pump was just as good, but there has to be some deciding factor.I hope this review helps you in your selection of a nice vacuum pump!!", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States September 21, 2019', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Works great. So unfortunately, the bag geared more for travel would have been great getting me to my destination, but it wouldn‚Äôt have been great as a day-backpack in that regard (plus the back splitting in half when you are adding things as you are out and about would have been awkward and inconvenient). Oh, and it didn‚Äôt have the tissue pocket, which was another brilliant feature I will DEFINITELY use. So even though most people are buying and reviewing the bags I purchased for work/school purposes, this review is for anyone looking for a great bag for travel. I ordered two styles as I really liked both and couldn‚Äôt decide. While I liked the look of the quilted bag more, I decided it wouldn‚Äôt serve my travel needs because all of those cute exterior pockets meant that the main compartment was a bit smaller. I believe the quilted is a 17 in and the other (the one I kept) is the 15.6. Neither is labeled in the tag or on my Amazon purchase list though, so I wish the company did a better job with that, but the difference isn‚Äôt enough to make a huge impact if you aren‚Äôt concerned about fitting a certain-sized laptop. Both bags have many similar features (like the USB port, lots of internal pockets, and the external tissue pocket), which was great. What I like about the bag I kept is that there is a frame of some sort around the opening compartment, so it locks open to a degree, making it much easier to pack as you don‚Äôt have to use one hand to always hold the bag open to pack and unpack. Because of that frame, when it is closed, it would be much more difficult to sneak open the main compartment by someone looking for an easy pickpocketing opportunity, and there is also enough room to attach a small lock to the main-compartment zippers for added security. The quilted bag had no possibility for this and could be unzipped and a hand quickly inserted if the wearer wasn‚Äôt paying attention. There isn‚Äôt a way to secure the three exterior zippered pockets on either bag. While the colors I chose will certainly get dirty quickly, it feels sturdy enough to spot clean. I may regret the color choice as the USB port makes it impossible to throw in the washing machine or fully soak, but I will have to cross that bridge when I get there. I really love the colors and that it will go with almost all outerwear I own. This bag (both bags) will fit easily under seat on a plane and still allow ample foot space. I used it for a 9 day visit to my sister, and am excited to use it on an upcoming international trip. There are lots of internal pockets, which is great for organizing your items (but also can make it difficult to remember where items were placed because there are SO MANY pockets. The containers are varied, although it only contains one spray bottle, I bought another one as I wanted more than one, but this is just a personal choice.I have read that the containers leak when traveling. They do NOT leak just sitting on the counter, btw. However, leaking during a flight is NORMAL. The pressure changes within the plane and the liquids expand causing the leaks.However, I learned a simple trick that usually keeps liquids from seeping out. First, only fill the containers a maximum of 2/3 full. Then take a plastic bag and cut squares that will cover the threads where the tops screw on. (Any plastic will work, even grocery bags) Open the container and place this plastic square over the opening, covering all the threads. Then screw the lid over the plastic. This creates a better seal and usually keeps leaks from happening. In fact, I have never had a leak using this method.If you have a spray bottle, you simply remove the spray lid, and replace it with a regular lid. Take the spray lid with you and then when you reach your destination, replace the regular lid with the spray top.', 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States July 7, 2013', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '4.0 out of 5 stars Great Value, Travels Well, Bottles are Higher Quality Than the Bag', 'author': 'Rebekah', 'rating': 4, 'content': "The bottles are great--they're very soft and flexible (for easy squeezing!) and have good size and top variation. One of them was not completely airtight when tested; however, I have travelled extensively with them (including long-haul flights) and have had no issue with leakage whatsoever; I also haven't noticed product drying out. The little containers with the screw top lids are rigid plastic, not squeezable, and are nice to put small amounts of liquid make-up or lotions in. Loved having the variety of the containers.", 'timestamp': 'Reviewed in the United States April 14, 2014', 'is_verified': True}, {'title': '1.0 out of 5 stars DESTROYED MY COMPUTER!!', 'author': 'Publisher', 'rating': 1, 'content': 'DESTROYED MY COMPUTER!!On April 5, 2018, I flew from Fargo, ND to Miami, FL, for a monthly business trip. The week prior, I had purchased the "Travel Smart Travel Bottle Set‚Äù because it purported to ‚Äúconform with TSA guidelines‚Äù and be ‚Äúideal for shampoo, conditioners, hairspray, lotions, creams, etc.‚Äù Equally important is that it ‚Äúships from and sold by Amazon.com <http://amazon.com>.‚Äù I‚Äôve been an Amazon customer for over 15 years, and it has come to be my most trusted place to shop. And as an Amazon Prime member, I needed this kit to arrive fast as it was eligible for two day delivery, and so I chose this one. And boy do I regret it.I filled the bottles and jars with my liquids and gels and sealed them properly, placed them in the bag they came in, zipped it, and then placed my MacBook Pro laptop--which is my primary source of business and personal communication and work--in my carry-on backpack laptop sleeve. I then packed other important items, including this new travel bottle set, on top, so that I could take it out for TSA screening and it would not be crushed.I arrived in Miami and stayed at a friends‚Äô apartment on Miami Beach. The following morning, I woke up to start work on presentation that I was to give in a couple days, only to find that my computer screen was sticky and hard to open, and the computer was not on, which didn‚Äôt make sense, since the battery had been charged the day before. I tried to turn it on, and nothing happened‚Äîtotally dead. I showed it to my friends, and the husband discovered that there was something gooey in the outlets and portals, which smelled minty.This is when I realized that my new Conair toiletries bag, which I had removed the night before and noticed it was sticky on the inside, had leaked into the computer! I then inspected each container and noticed that my shampoo bottle, which I had properly sealed upon packing, had nonetheless leaked at least an inch of its contents, and one of the small containers with the twist-on cap, which had a liquid eye cream substance in it upon packing and closing, had almost completely drained out. These were the two most ‚Äúliquid‚Äù of my toiletries. The other creams seemed gooey enough to stay put in their jars, but not the actual liquids.This was a tragic but totally foreseeable incident on the companies part‚Äîthat is Amazon and Conair‚Äî where the toiletry bag is placed on top of everything else‚Äîwhere it should be--but the liquids leaked from their sealed containers, and then leaked through the zipped bag that nonetheless comes with gaps and small holes. This hole must have been situated exactly on top of my computer portals.So began an awful and expensive couple weeks of visits to the Apple Store in Miami Beach and the nearby Apple authorized dealer, Proatics, feeling too much pressure due to the extremely expensive diagnostic bill I‚Äôd been given to fix it ($1650 was the first estimate I received from the Apple authorized dealer, having diagnosed it as Stage 4 liquid damage that had fried everything but my hard drive, which he was thankfully able to extract before the shampoo reached it.) I gave my presentation as best I could, though was very stressed out and drained from this experience, having luckily emailed myself a draft of my presentation, which I was then able to do a cursory edit on a friend\'s computer. But beyond that I was not able to do other work throughout this time, and so have effectively lost three weeks in this mess.On Wednesday, April 11, I flew to the Twin Cities and made several visits to the Apple store there, trying to decide what was the best course of action. Their workers confirmed the stage 4 liquid damage from shampoo, but advised given the high cost of sending it to repair, that I replace the used and damaged machine with a new one.I contacted Amazon.com twice about this incident, including full documentation, and have received two cursory emails from their Executive Customer Relations person, Gabor Kiss, expressing sympathy but saying that it is not their responsibility, but Conair‚Äôs, and I must contact them. Kiss also refunded the $12 and change for the travel kit, and gave me a $30 (!) Amazon credit in response to my request for $2,417.58 of actual, documented expenses incurred to replace my computer. Kiss stated in his emails that to Amazon, ‚Äúproduct safety is extremely important‚Äù and they are ‚Äúreally sorry‚Äù to hear about this incident. But a $30 credit gives the lie to both those statements.I have since spoken with a corporate malpractice law firm, who looked at the case and advises me that given the well over 100 negative reviews that this product has ‚Äî which we have since gone back to read and I even sent them as attachments to Amazon ‚Äî that Amazon and Conair have been on notice for five years that this product ‚Äúleaks on the first time‚Äù, ‚Äúcracks‚Äù, ‚Äúran all over my bag‚Äù, ‚Äúopens in the air‚Äù, is ‚Äújunk‚Äù and ‚Äúothers be warned,‚Äù to quote just a few titles. Hundreds of customers have been diligent in documenting the dangers of this product, some even posting pictures.But what was Gabor Kiss and Amazon‚Äôs response? he wrote "Reviews while helpful, may not speak towards the exact same manufacturing batch as your specific unit.‚Äù So in other words, it\'s a total crapshoot what you‚Äôre going to get with this product, despite it leaking over five years. Apparently Amazon feels no responsibility to pull a product that is clearly harming their customers, year after year, ruining their business trips and vacations, and putting their expensive electronics, important documents, clothes and other personal effects at risk each time we fly. Apparently Amazon (and Conair) have never heard of such a thing as quality control. Or products liability. And all the effort that we customers put into rating these products really doesnt matter to them, because nobody on their end is checking, or taking us seriously.Since this whole fiasco began, I and my family have refrained from purchasing anything from your company. They should pay for this well-documented damage, and yet they continue to dodge responsibility . Because of it, they have lost a very loyal customer, since I am now shopping online at Walmart, Barnes and Noble, iTunes, You Tube, etc. My family (and my lawyer) we surprised by their shady treatment. reviews: [{'title': '5.0 out of 5 stars Small but so functional', 'author': 'Taterlayne', 'rating': 5, 'content': "Whenever I travel, I like to tuck a collapsible bag in my suitcase because I always end up needing a bit more space. I immediately opened the nylon zipper to reveal the largest size bag. Sturdy strap handles well sewn. Several storage options inside and out, and several zip areas. The outer pocket becomes an inner pocket on the other side with a flip and zip. A VERY inspired and unique design! I was excited to take this handy bag traveling or to markets or on trips... except for a fatal flaw.The zipper to transform this bag from the largest size to the smaller size is nylon. It is a LOT to zip, nearly twice around, and there is a lot of fabric to tuck away to keep it out of the zipper path. I zipped it about a third of the way around, and it would not go any further, and it wouldn\'t unzip either! I didn\'t want to force it and break the zipper, as my hands are not strong. So it was stuck, and I was frustrated. Husband was finally able to carefully free it, and I could zip it the rest of the way. Phew! A metal zipper, although it would add weight, would also add confidence in transforming the bag. Perhaps with use the extra fabric won\'t be a problem. But will the zipper hold up? The zipper becomes the bottom "seam", so it\'s taking all the weight of what you put in it at the smaller sizes. We shall see...You need the bag to be fully open to fold it back into its smallest form. So that zipper will get lots of use. It is a heavier nylon, but I think a metal zip would give more lifetime to the bag.Zipping it back into its smallest size is a bit confusing, and requires a lot of futzing to get everything folded and flipped and zipped. The photos help a little, but a video would be better, even if it\'s awkward and long.So if you are using this bag at its largest size only, I say it\'s amazing. At the next smaller size, only the zipper stands in your way. I didn\'t try the smallest bag size, I need to look at the photos again. It involves the snaps at the sides.Getting it back into compact travel square is a challenge that is worth it for travel.So although this bag needs a few changes, the basic design is incredible.
